{"title_page": "Waikato (New Zealand electorate)", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand electorate}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n[[image:Waikato electorate, 2014.svg|thumb|right|Waikato electorate boundaries used since the {{NZ election link|2014}}]]\n'''Waikato''' is the name of a current electorate in the [[New Zealand Parliament]].  The electorate first existed from 1871 to 1963, and then from 1969 to 1996 when [[Mixed-member proportional representation|MMP]] was introduced.  The current electorate was re-established for the {{NZ election link|2008}} and has been represented by [[Tim van de Molen]] for the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] since the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]].\n\n==Population centres==\nThrough an amendment in the Electoral Act in 1965, the number of electorates in the [[South Island]] was fixed at 25, an increase of one since the 1962 electoral redistribution.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|pp=108, 111, 112}} It was accepted that through the more rapid population growth in the [[North Island]], the number of its electorates would continue to increase, and to keep proportionality, three new electorates were allowed for in the 1967 electoral redistribution for the next election.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|p=111}} In the North Island, five electorates were newly created and one electorate was reconstituted (Waikato) while three electorates were abolished.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|pp=107, 111}} In the South Island, three electorates were newly created and one electorate was reconstituted while three electorates were abolished.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|pp=108, 112}} The overall effect of the required changes was highly disruptive to existing electorates, with all but three electorates having their boundaries altered.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|pp=111f}} These changes came into effect with the {{NZ election link|1969}}.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|p=111}}\n\nThe electorate was recreated after the 2006 census, as the successor to the former {{NZ electorate link|Piako}} electorate. Piako has been pulled north to account for changes both in [[Auckland]] (where population growth has pulled the boundary of [[Port Waikato (New Zealand electorate)|Port Waikato]] around the [[Waikato River]]), and in the central North Island, where several electorates went into the boundary review under quota, forcing their boundaries further north. It has lost the towns of [[Te Aroha]] to [[Coromandel (New Zealand electorate)|Coromandel]] and [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]] to [[Taup\u014d (New Zealand electorate)|Taup\u014d]], and in exchange gained the rural and semi-urban areas around [[Hamilton East (New Zealand electorate)|Hamilton East]], and [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]], [[Te Kauwhata]] and [[Meremere]] from Port Waikato. It was significantly altered at the 2020 redistribution, losing its entire northwestern section to the recreated {{NZ electorate link|Port Waikato}} electorate, but gaining a large area around [[Te Aroha]] from {{NZ electorate link|Coromandel}} and gaining smaller populations from {{NZ electorate link|Hamilton West}} around [[Horotiu]] and {{NZ electorate link|Taup\u014d}} around [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]], [[Put\u0101ruru]] and [[T\u012brau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vote.nz/assets/Boundary-Review/REPORT-OF-THE-REPRESENTATION-COMMISSION-2020.pdf |title=Report of the Representation Commission 2020 |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Waikato electorate was first contested in the {{NZ election link|1871}}.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=165}} [[James McPherson (New Zealand politician)|James McPherson]] was elected, but he resigned again on 20 December 1871.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=124}} [[William Jackson (New Zealand politician)|William Jackson]] won the resulting {{By-election link|Waikato|1872}} (held on 1 March). He retired at the end of the parliamentary term in 1875.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=116}}  [[Frederick Whitaker]] won 5 January [[1875\u20131876 New Zealand general election|1876 election]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=147}}  In the {{NZ election link|1879}}, Whitaker contested the {{NZ electorate link|Eden}} electorate but was beaten by [[Joseph Tole]].<ref name=\"DNZB Whitaker\">{{DNZB|Stone|R. C. J. |1w17|Whitaker, Frederick \u2013 Biography|14 March 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=144}}\n\nThe Waikato electorate was won by [[John Blair Whyte]] in the 1879 election, who served for eleven years until 1890 when he retired. Whyte was appointed to the [[New Zealand Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] in the following year.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|pp=87, 147}} [[John Bryce]], who first became an MHR (Member of the House of Representatives) during the [[4th New Zealand Parliament|4th Parliament]], succeeded Whyte in the {{NZ election link|1890}}, but he resigned in the following year.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=97}}  The resulting {{By-election link|Waikato|1891}} was won by [[Edward Lake (politician)|Edward Lake]], who retired at the end of the parliamentary term in 1893.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=211}}\n\nThe {{NZ election link|1893}} was won by [[Alfred Cadman]] for the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]], who had been an MP in various electorates since 1881. At the next election in {{NZ election link year|1896}}, Cadman successfully contested the {{NZ electorate link|Ohinemuri}} electorate.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=99}} The Waikato electorate was won by [[Frederic Lang]] in 1896, who represented the electorate until his defeat by the Liberal Party's [[Henry Greenslade]] in the {{NZ election link|1905}}.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=119}} Greenslade held the electorate until [[1911 New Zealand general election|1911]],{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=109}} when he was defeated by the [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform]] candidate [[Alexander Young (New Zealand politician)|Alexander Young]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=149}}\n\nYoung won the subsequent elections in {{NZ election link year|1914}} and {{NZ election link year|1919}}. In the {{NZ election link|1922}}, he successfully contested the newly formed {{NZ electorate link|Hamilton}} electorate.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=149}}  Young was succeeded by the Liberal candidate [[Frederick Lye]] in the Waikato electorate in 1922.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=121}}  At the {{NZ election link|1925}}, Lye was defeated by Reform's [[Daniel Stewart Reid]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=134}} Lye in turn defeated Reid at the {{NZ election link|1928}}, but this time standing for the [[United Party (New Zealand)|United Party]]. The [[United\u2013Reform Coalition]] was established just before the {{NZ election link|1931}} and Lye was again successful.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=121}} In the {{NZ election link|1935}}, Lye was beaten by [[Robert Coulter (New Zealand politician)|Robert Coulter]] of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=102}} Coulter served only one term in Waikato, as he was defeated by the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] candidate [[Stan Goosman]] in the {{NZ election link|1938}}. Goosman also won the {{NZ election link|1943}}, but successfully contested the {{NZ election link|1946}} in the newly formed {{NZ electorate link|Piako}} electorate.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=109}}\n\nGoosman was succeeded in Waikato by National's [[Geoffrey Sim]] in 1946.{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=139}} Sim held the electorate until it was abolished in 1963, when he contested Piako instead.{{sfn|Wilson|1985}}\n\nThe Waikato electorate was re-established in [[1969 New Zealand general election|1969]]. The first representative was National's [[Lance Adams-Schneider]], who had previously represented the Hamilton electorate. Adams-Schneider retired from Parliament in 1981 and became Ambassador of New Zealand to the [[List of ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States|United States]] in the following year.{{sfn|Wilson|1985}}  Adams-Schneider was succeeded by National's [[Simon Upton]], who won the {{NZ election link|1981}} and started his long parliamentary career with one term in Waikato. Upton contested the {{NZ electorate link|Raglan}} in the {{NZ election link|1984}} and was succeeded by National's [[Rob Storey]] in Waikato. Storey held the electorate until it was abolished with the introduction of [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed-member proportional]] voting in [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996]]. It was re-established for the 2008 election.\n\n[[Lindsay Tisch]] was the MP for Piako from its re-establishment in [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002]], and became the MP for Waikato at the {{NZ election link|2008}}.<ref name=\"2008 Waikato\" /> Tisch was confirmed in the {{NZ election link|2011}}.<ref name=\"2011 Waikato\" />\n\nIn June 2016, Tisch announced that he would not stand at the [[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/81167337/mp-lindsay-tisch-not-to-seek-reelection|accessdate=27 September 2017|title=MP Lindsay Tisch not to seek re-election|date=20 June 2016|publisher=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> and the seat was won by Tim van de Molen, retaining it for the National Party.\n\nIn the 20th century Waikato was a safe [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] seat; and three of the five National Party members of parliament for Waikato were cabinet ministers.\n\n===Members of Parliament===\n'''Key'''\n\n{{Party index link|Independent politician}} {{Party index link|Conservative (New Zealand)}} {{Party index link|New Zealand Liberal Party}} {{Party index link|Reform Party (New Zealand)}} {{Party index link|United Party (New Zealand)}} {{Party index link|New Zealand Labour Party}} {{Party index link|New Zealand National Party}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| width=125 |'''Election'''\n| width=175 colspan=2 |'''Winner'''\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1871}}\n| width=5 rowspan=1 bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}} |\n| [[James McPherson (New Zealand politician)|Jame