{"title_page": "The Oak Ridge Boys discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist       = [[The Oak Ridge Boys]]\n|Image        = OAK RIDGE BOYS.jpg\n|Caption      = \n|Studio       = 31\n|Compilation  = 14\n|EP           = \n|Live         = 1\n|Singles      = 63\n|Music videos = 21\n|Option          = \n|Option name     = \n|Option color    = blue\n|2Option         = 17\n|2Option name    = No.1 Single\n|2Option color   = orange\n|References   = \n}}\n\n'''[[The Oak Ridge Boys]]''' is an American musical group. Originally a [[gospel music|gospel]] group, The Oak Ridge Boys switched its focus to [[country music]] in the mid-1970s, releasing a string of hit albums and singles that lasted into the early 1990s. Their [[discography]] comprises thirty-one [[studio album]]s and fifty-six [[single (music)|single]]s. Their highest-selling album is 1981's ''[[Fancy Free (The Oak Ridge Boys album)|Fancy Free]]'', which is certified double-platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\nOf The Oak Ridge Boys' singles, seventeen reached Number One on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country singles charts. Two of these songs, \"Elvira\" and \"Bobbie Sue\", were also Top 40 pop and Adult Contemporary hits, and the former is certified platinum as a single. Four additional singles (\"Sail Away\", \"Dream On\", \"Heart of Mine\", and \"Fancy Free\") also entered the AC charts, while \"[[So Fine (Johnny Otis song)|So Fine]]\" and \"American Made\" both made the 70s on the pop charts.\n\n==Studio albums==\n\n===1950s===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Oak Ridge Quartet''\n| \n* Release date: 1958\n* Label: [[Cadence Records]]\n* Formats: [[LP record|LP]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Sing and Shout''\n|\n* Release date: 1959\n* Label: Skylite Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Oak Ridge Quartet''\n|\n* Release date: 1959\n* Label: [[Checker Records]]\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n|}\n\n===1960s===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Master Showman of Song''\n|\n* Release date: 1960\n* Label: [[Starday Records]]\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Go Out to the Program''\n|\n* Release date: 1960\n* Label: Skylite\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''You'll Never Walk Alone''\n|\n* Release date: 1961\n* Label: Skylite\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''He Whispers Sweet Peace to Me''\n|\n* Release date: 1962\n* Label: Skylite\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''With Sounds of Nashville''\n|\n* Release date: 1962\n* Label: [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Folk Minded Spirituals for Spiritual Minded Folk''\n|\n* Release date: 1963\n* Label: Warner Bros. Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Together''<br><small>(with The Harvesters)</small>\n|\n* Release date: 1964\n* Label: [[Festival Records]]\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Sing for You''\n|\n* Release date: 1964\n* Label: Skylite Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Singing the Gospel''\n|\n* Release date: 1964\n* Label: Stateswood Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''I Wouldn't Take Nothing for My Journey Now''\n|\n* Release date: 1964\n* Label: Skylite Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Sensational Oak Ridge Boys<br>from Nashville Tennessee''\n|\n* Release date: 1965\n* Label: Starday Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Solid Gospel Sound<br>of the Oak Ridge Quartet''\n|\n* Release date: 1965\n* Label: Skylite Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''River of Life''\n|\n* Release date: 1966\n* Label: Skylite Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Sing Serve Life''<br><small>(with Smitty Gatlin)</small>\n|\n* Release date: 1966\n* Label: Skylite Record