{"title_page": "Daniel Zovatto", "text_new": "{{short description|Costa Rican film and television actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Daniel Zovatto\n| image              = [[File:Daniel-zovatto-actor.jpg|thumb|]]\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1991|6|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| yearsactive        = 2012\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Zovatto''' (born June 28, 1991) is a Costa Rican American film and television actor. Since 2012, he has starred in films of the horror genre, ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]'' (2013), ''[[It Follows]]'' (2014), and ''[[Don't Breathe]]'' (2016), as well as the romantic comedy ''[[Laggies]]'' (2014). Zovatto made his television debut in 2014, guest starring in an episode of ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'' He has since held recurring roles as Gideon LeMarchal in ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]'' (2014), and Jack in ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]'' (2016).\n\n== Early life and career ==\nDaniel Zovatto Blanco was born in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]], on June 28, 1991 to Sylvia Blanco.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} After moving to [[New York City]], Zovatto initially pursued theatre and was cast in a short film, ''The Return''. He later moved to [[Los Angeles]], where he made his feature film debut in the 2013 horror movie, ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]'', as Johnny. The independent film, released on May 3, 2013, was directed by [[Larry Fessenden]], and marked Zovatto's first main role in a film. Later that year, he starred as Neils Hirsch in the horror drama film ''[[Innocence (2013 film)|Innocence]]'', opposite [[Linus Roache]] and [[Stephanie March]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/daniel-zovatto-57925246/#biography|title=Daniel Zovatto: Biography and Filmography|work=[[Hollywood.com]]|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Zovatto made his television debut in season one episode of ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', \"[[Seeds (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Seeds]]\". From May to October 2014, Zovatto had a 3 episode arc in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC's]] soap opera drama series ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]''. His character, Gideon LeMarchal, dates [[Charlotte Grayson]] ([[Christa B. Allen]]) in the [[Revenge (season 3)|third]] and [[Revenge (season 3)|fourth]] seasons of the series. Zovatto's next film project was the romantic comedy ''[[Laggies]]'', in the role of Junior, alongside actors including [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Keira Knightley]], and [[Mark Webber]]. This was followed with his breakthrough role in the 2014 supernatural horror film, ''[[It Follows]]'', as Greg Hannigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/fear-walking-dead-casts-daniel-zovatto/|title=Fear the Walking Dead casts It Follows star Daniel Zovatto  |author=Persaud, Christine|publisher=[[Digital Trends]]|date=January 29, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> The film received widespread critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-exotic-marigold-778866|title=U.K. Box Office: 'Exotic Marigold' Sequel Topples 'Fifty Shades'|author=Ritman, Alex|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 3, 2015|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nZovatto played a leading role in ''[[Don't Breathe]]'', a horror film directed by [[Fede \u00c1lvarez]]. Cast as the character Money, the film premiered on March 12, 2016, at the [[South by Southwest]] film festival, and received a theatrical release in the U.S. on August 26, 2016. Although the film is set in [[Detroit]], it was primarily shot in [[Hungary]], with only a few views of the Detroit ruins shot in Detroit.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/markets-festivals/dont-breathe-review-sxsw-1201729010/|title=SXSW Film Review: \u2018Don\u2019t Breathe\u2019|author=Dennis, Harvey|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 13, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Since 2016, Zovatto has had a recurring role on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC's]] horror drama series ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]'', during the show's [[Fear the Walking Dead (season 2)|second season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/fear-the-walking-dead-cast-daniel-zovatto-the-walking-dead-1201692439/|title=\u2018Fear The Walking Dead\u2019 Casts Daniel Zovatto In Recurring Role|author=Petski, Denise|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> While he does not appear in the premiere episode of season two, \"Monster\", Jack (Zovatto) is heard conversing with Alicia Clark ([[Alycia Debnam-Carey]]), after the latter responds to his [[Distress signal|distress calls over the radio]]. Debnam-Carey and Zovatto's characters share a romance in the succeeding episodes \"Blood in the Streets\" and \"Captive\", despite Jack and accomplices of his have kidnapped Clark and her stepfather.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/fear-the-walking-dead-star-daniel-zovatto-on-jack-and-alicias-relationship/|title=\u2018Fear the Walking Dead\u2019 Star Talks Jack and Alicia\u2019s Relationship|author=Ge, Linda|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Film\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012 \n| ''The Return'' \n| Sebastian \n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\n| ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]''\n| Johnny\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\n| ''[[Innocence (2013 film)|Innocence]]'' \n| Neils Hirsch \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Laggies]]''\n| Junior\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[It Follows]]''\n| Greg Hannigan \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[Don't Breathe]]''\n| Money\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]''\n| Jonah Ruiz\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Newness]]''\n| Oren\n|\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Television\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n| Seth Dormer\n| Guest; episode: \"[[Seeds (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Seeds]]\" \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]''\n| Gideon LeMarchal\n| Recurring; episodes: \"Execution\", \"Renaissance\", \"Disclosure\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]''\n| Jack\n| Recurring; episodes: \"Monster\", \"[[Blood in the Streets (Fear the Walking Dead)|Blood in the Streets]]\", \"Captive\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[The Deleted]]''\n| Logan\n| Recurring<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web | url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/orange-is-the-new-black-madeline-brewer-series-regulars-cast-brett-easton-ellis-the-deleted-1201800024/ | title=\u2018Orange Is The New Black\u2019s Madeline Brewer Among Seven Cast In Bret Easton Ellis\u2019 \u2018The Deleted\u2019 | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 8, 2016 | accessdate=December 19, 2016 | author=Petski, Denise}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Dimension 404]]''\n| Zach\n| Episode: \"Cinethrax\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2018\n| ''[[Here and Now (2018 TV series)|Here and Now]]''\n| Ram\u00f3n\n| Main cast\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019\n| ''[[Penny Dreadful: City of Angels]]''\n| Detective Tiago Vega\n| Main cast\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|4683167}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{instagram|thatzovatt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zovatto, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican male film actors]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican male television actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Costa Rican film and television actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Daniel Zovatto\n| image                 = \n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1991|6|28}}\n| birth_place           = [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]]\n| occupation            = Actor\n| yearsactive           = 2012\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Zovatto''' (born June 28, 1991) is a Costa Rican American film and television actor. Since 2012, he has starred in films of the horror genre, ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]'' (2013), ''[[It Follows]]'' (2014), and ''[[Don't Breathe]]'' (2016), as well as the romantic comedy ''[[Laggies]]'' (2014). Zovatto made his television debut in 2014, guest starring in an episode of ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'' He has since held recurring roles as Gideon LeMarchal in ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]'' (2014), and Jack in ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]'' (2016).\n\n== Early life and career ==\nDaniel Zovatto Blanco was born in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]], on June 28, 1991 to Sylvia Blanco.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} After moving to [[New York City]], Zovatto initially pursued theatre and was cast in a short film, ''The Return''. He later moved to [[Los Angeles]], where he made his feature film debut in the 2013 horror movie, ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]'', as Johnny. The independent film, released on May 3, 2013, was directed by [[Larry Fessenden]], and marked Zovatto's first main role in a film. Later that year, he starred as Neils Hirsch in the horror drama film ''[[Innocence (2013 film)|Innocence]]'', opposite [[Linus Roache]] and [[Stephanie March]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/daniel-zovatto-57925246/#biography|title=Daniel Zovatto: Biography and Filmography|work=[[Hollywood.com]]|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Zovatto made his television debut in season one episode of ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', \"[[Seeds (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Seeds]]\". From May to October 2014, Zovatto had a 3 episode arc in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC's]] soap opera drama series ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]''. His character, Gideon LeMarchal, dates [[Charlotte Grayson]] ([[Christa B. Allen]]) in the [[Revenge (season 3)|third]] and [[Revenge (season 3)|fourth]] seasons of the series. Zovatto's next film project was the romantic comedy ''[[Laggies]]'', in the role of Junior, alongside actors including [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Keira Knightley]], and [[Mark Webber]]. This was followed with his breakthrough role in the 2014 supernatural horror film, ''[[It Follows]]'', as Greg Hannigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/fear-walking-dead-casts-daniel-zovatto/|title=Fear the Walking Dead casts It Follows star Daniel Zovatto  |author=Persaud, Christine|publisher=[[Digital Trends]]|date=January 29, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> The film received widespread critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-exotic-marigold-778866|title=U.K. Box Office: 'Exotic Marigold' Sequel Topples 'Fifty Shades'|author=Ritman, Alex|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 3, 2015|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nZovatto played a leading role in ''[[Don't Breathe]]'', a horror film directed by [[Fede \u00c1lvarez]]. Cast as the character Money, the film premiered on March 12, 2016, at the [[South by Southwest]] film festival, and received a theatrical release in the U.S. on August 26, 2016. Although the film is set in [[Detroit]], it was primarily shot in [[Hungary]], with only a few views of the Detroit ruins shot in Detroit.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/markets-festivals/dont-breathe-review-sxsw-1201729010/|title=SXSW Film Review: \u2018Don\u2019t Breathe\u2019|author=Dennis, Harvey|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 13, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Since 2016, Zovatto has had a recurring role on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC's]] horror drama series ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]'', during the show's [[Fear the Walking Dead (season 2)|second season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/fear-the-walking-dead-cast-daniel-zovatto-the-walking-dead-1201692439/|title=\u2018Fear The Walking Dead\u2019 Casts Daniel Zovatto In Recurring Role|author=Petski, Denise|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> While he does not appear in the premiere episode of season two, \"Monster\", Jack (Zovatto) is heard conversing with Alicia Clark ([[Alycia Debnam-Carey]]), after the latter responds to his [[Distress signal|distress calls over the radio]]. Debnam-Carey and Zovatto's characters share a romance in the succeeding episodes \"Blood in the Streets\" and \"Captive\", despite Jack and accomplices of his have kidnapped Clark and her stepfather.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/fear-the-walking-dead-star-daniel-zovatto-on-jack-and-alicias-relationship/|title=\u2018Fear the Walking Dead\u2019 Star Talks Jack and Alicia\u2019s Relationship|author=Ge, Linda|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Film\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012 \n| ''The Return'' \n| Sebastian \n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\n| ''[[Beneath (2013 film)|Beneath]]''\n| Johnny\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\n| ''[[Innocence (2013 film)|Innocence]]'' \n| Neils Hirsch \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Laggies]]''\n| Junior\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[It Follows]]''\n| Greg Hannigan \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[Don't Breathe]]''\n| Money\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]''\n| Jonah Ruiz\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Newness]]''\n| Oren\n|\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Television\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n| Seth Dormer\n| Guest; episode: \"[[Seeds (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Seeds]]\" \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[Revenge (TV series)|Revenge]]''\n| Gideon LeMarchal\n| Recurring; episodes: \"Execution\", \"Renaissance\", \"Disclosure\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]''\n| Jack\n| Recurring; episodes: \"Monster\", \"[[Blood in the Streets (Fear the Walking Dead)|Blood in the Streets]]\", \"Captive\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[The Deleted]]''\n| Logan\n| Recurring<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web | url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/orange-is-the-new-black-madeline-brewer-series-regulars-cast-brett-easton-ellis-the-deleted-1201800024/ | title=\u2018Orange Is The New Black\u2019s Madeline Brewer Among Seven Cast In Bret Easton Ellis\u2019 \u2018The Deleted\u2019 | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 8, 2016 | accessdate=December 19, 2016 | author=Petski, Denise}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| ''[[Dimension 404]]''\n| Zach\n| Episode: \"Cinethrax\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2018\n| ''[[Here and Now (2018 TV series)|Here and Now]]''\n| Ram\u00f3n\n| Main cast\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019\n| ''[[Penny Dreadful: City of Angels]]''\n| Detective Tiago Vega\n| Main cast\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|4683167}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{instagram|thatzovatt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zovatto, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican male film actors]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican male television actors]]\n", "name_user": "Laumber", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add image from wikimedia.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Zovatto"}
{"title_page": "Frank B. Walsh", "text_new": "{{tone|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Frank B. Walsh\n| image =\n| birth_date = October 18, 1895\n| birth_place = Oxbow, Saskatchewan, Canada\n| death_date = November 27, 1978\n| death_place = Baltimore, Maryland, United States of America\n| nationality = American-Canadian\n| education = Queen's University\nUniversity of Manitoba Medical School\n| occupation = Neuro-ophthalmologist\n}}\n\n'''Frank Burton Walsh''' (October 18, 1895, [[Oxbow, Saskatchewan]] \u2013 November 27, 1978, [[Baltimore, Maryland]]) was a Canadian-American ophthalmologist known for his work in [[neuro-ophthalmology]].<ref name=EyeWorldRef>{{cite journal|last1=Angelucci|first1=Diane|title=Groundbreaking neuro-ophthalmologist honored|journal=EyeWorld|date=February 2001|url=http://www.eyeworld.org/article.php?sid=1115}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[http://www.ascrs.org/honorees/frank-b-walsh-md Frank B. Walsh, MD | ASCRS]</ref> For the main duration of his career, Walsh worked as a neuro-ophthalmologist at the [[Wilmer Eye Institute|Wilmer Eye Institute of Johns Hopkins Hospital]]. Walsh is most well known for his textbook ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'', which contains a compilation of Walsh's case reports and the conclusions he drew from them. Originally published in 1947, the textbook has many updated versions and is still a premier text in the field of neuro-ophthalmology. Walsh is considered by many to be the father of neuro-ophthalmology due to his contributions to the field.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\">{{Cite journal|last=Udvarhelyi|first=George B.|date=1985-02-01|title=Frank B. Walsh M.D. The father of neuroophthalmology|journal=Surgical Neurology|language=English|volume=23|issue=2|pages=93\u201395|doi=10.1016/0090-3019(85)90325-8|issn=0090-3019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nFrank Burton Walsh was born in Oxbow, [[Saskatchewan]], Canada on October 18, 1895.  He comes from English-Irish descent. While he was in school, he participated in musical activities such as piano and clarinet. He also played sports, which included football, baseball and hockey. His other hobbies included hunting and fishing.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|url= |title=A personal sketch of Frank Burton Walsh |language=en|doi=10.1016/0039-6257(83)90179-0|volume=28|journal=Survey of Ophthalmology|pages=50\u201354 | last1 = Coston | first1 = Tullos O.|year=1983 }}</ref>\n[[File:Queen's University from the air 1919.jpg|thumb|Queen's University]]\nWalsh began his college education at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] (Canada) in 1913. During his time at Queen's, Walsh had to enlist for [[World War I]], where he became a lieutenant in the Canadian Army. Due to a wound at the [[Battle of Ypres]], he was sent home with an honorable discharge. He then went to the [[University of Manitoba College of Medicine]], where he received his medical degree in 1921.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhile working in private practice, Walsh started to gain interest in [[ophthalmology]]. Around this time, the Wilmer Institute of Ophthalmology in Baltimore, Maryland opened, so Walsh wrote to Dr. Wilmer asking for a resident position. Dr. Wilmer was extremely impressed with Walsh and granted him as a position as a first year resident. Walsh moved to Baltimore with his wife, Marion, and his two children, McMurty and Walter, in 1930 at the age of 35. By his fourth year, Walsh was the chief resident. He was almost 40 years old when he finished his residency.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMarion died in 1960 of a brain tumor, and Walsh remarried several years later to Josie. Josie worked as the head surgical nurse at the Winnipeg General Hospital.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early medical career ===\n[[File:Appendectomy at the French Hospital in Tiflis (Dartigues 1919).JPG|thumb|Example of an appendectomy]]\nFollowing Walsh's graduation from the [[University of Manitoba College of Medicine]] in 1921, he spent nine years in general practice.<ref name=\":1\" /> For the first two years, he was employed as a house officer at [[Winnipeg General Hospital]]. In 1923, Walsh moved to [[Estevan|Estavan, Saskatchewan]], where he delivered babies and performed [[Appendectomy|appendectomies]] as a general practitioner. In 1930 Walsh went back to school for ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\n=== Career in Neuro-Ophthalmology ===\nDuring Walsh's residency at the Wilmer Eye Institute, Walsh would see patients, teach, and host Saturday morning conferences that allowed ophthalmologists and neurologists to interact and discuss cases.<ref name=\":1\" /> Although Walsh worked in both [[neurology]] and [[ophthalmology]], he focused more on ophthalmology and was never formally a [[Neurology|neurologist]]. Walsh first entered the field of neuro-ophthalmology after approaching neuroscientist Dr. Frank Ford about performing joint research relating ophthalmology to the central nervous system during his last year of residency. Walsh's role in the research project included visiting many of Ford's patients and giving full ophthalmologic exams. Walsh then related his findings to many of the neurological findings of Ford. As Ford and Walsh's research project came to a close, Walsh realized he wanted to continue his studies in the relationship between neurology and ophthalmology. He published the ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' paper in 1936, which was the first research project in the field neuro-ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\nFollowing his residency, Walsh became a full-time staff member at the Wilmer Eye Institute of Johns Hopkins Hospital.<ref name=\":2\" /> Walsh left the Wilmer Eye Institute in 1945 to go into private practice in Baltimore, Maryland because of financial reasons.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWalsh is most well known for coauthoring ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' in 1947'','' which is the first textbook on neuro-ophthalmology. The book contained years of Walsh's observations, analysis, and cataloguing of diseases that affect the eye through the nervous system.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1960s, there were only 4 neuro-ophthalmologists in the United States. Over the course of Walsh's career, the number of neuro-ophthalmologists greatly increased, and many in the field looked to Walsh's work for their education and training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://professorships.jhu.edu/professorship/frank-b-walsh-professorship-neuro-ophthalmology/|title=Frank B. Walsh Professorship in Neuro-Ophthalmology - Named Deanships, Directorships, and Professorships|work=Named Deanships, Directorships, and Professorships|access-date=2017-04-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, following the death of his wife, Walsh returned as a full-time faculty member at Wilmer, where he remained until his death in 1978.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Research ===\n[[File:Medical instrument Eye Retinoscope.jpg|thumb|An example of a Retinoscope, one of the tools Walsh used to diagnose visual syndromes.]]\nWalsh's contributions to neuro-ophthalmology extended beyond his clinical work and teachings. Walsh documented and analyzed all of his clinical cases, and used them to perform research. He wrote down many of his major discoveries in published research papers. One of his most cited papers was on Tilted Disk Syndrome.<ref>{{Cite journal|url= |title=The Tilted Disk Syndrome  |doi=10.1016/0002-9394(76)90658-9|pmid=937453 |volume=82|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|pages=16\u201323 | last1 = Ellen Young | first1 = Sue|year=1976 }}</ref> He used many techniques, such as [[Retinoscopy]], Static and Kinetic Golmann Perimetry, [[Fluorescein angiography]], and ocular ultrasonography, to diagnose the syndrome. Walsh discovered several symptoms that could be used as diagnostic tools, such as an obliquely direct axis of the vertical disk.\n\nIn another one of his most cited articles, Walsh discussed whether [[oral contraceptives]] affected or complicated the parts of a patient's brain related to the eyes. Walsh came to the conclusion that, while birth control pills may cause hazards to visions in some extreme cases due to blood clotting, they did not normally cause problems with vision.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WALSH|first=F. B.|last2=CLARK|first2=D. B.|last3=THOMPSON|first3=R. S.|last4=NICHOLSON|first4=D. H.|date=1965-11-01|title=Oral Contraceptives and Neuro-Ophthalmologic Interest|url=http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamaophthalmology/fullarticle/628190|journal=Archives of Ophthalmology|language=en|volume=74|issue=5|pages=628\u2013640|doi=10.1001/archopht.1965.00970040630009|pmid=5321209|issn=0003-9950}}</ref>\n\n=== Accomplishments and honors ===\nWalsh received the following awards over his career:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* Lucian Howe Medal from [[American Ophthalmological Society]]\n* Jules Stein Award from the Jules Stein Institute at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n* Proctor Award from [[American Medical Association]] \n* Karl-Leibrecht Prize from German Ophthalmological Society\n* Proctor Medical Award from Association for Research in Ophthalmology\nIn addition to receiving these awards, Walsh also held positions within these groups:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* President and Member of the Board of Scientific Counselors at [[National Institutes of Health]]\n* President of the [[American Ophthalmological Society]] \n* Vice President of [[American Academy of Ophthalmology|American Academy of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology]]\n* Second Vice President of [[American Medical Association]] \nWalsh was also inducted as an honorary member in these Neurological and Ophthalmological societies:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* American Neurological Society\n* [[American Association of Neurological Surgeons]]\n* Canadian Ophthalmological Society\n* Australian Ophthalmological Society\n* German Ophthalmological Society\n* Irish Ophthalmological Society\n* Brazilian Ophthalmological Society\n* Sicilian Ophthalmological Society\n* Colombian Ophthalmological Society\n* Mexican Ophthalmological Society\n* Peruvian Ophthalmological Society\n* Uruguayan Ophthalmological Society\nWalsh received honorary Doctor  of Science degrees from the University of Western Australia and the University of Manitoba, and honorary Doctor of Law degrees from Queen's University and the Johns Hopkins University.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the October 1962 issue of the ''[[American Journal of Ophthalmology]]'', there was a special article about Walsh himself. In the article, Walsh is depicted as the leader of the field of neuro-ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Vail 717\u2013718\">{{Cite journal|last=Vail|first=Derrick|date=1962-10-01|title=Frank Burton Walsh, M.D.|url=http://www.ajo.com/article/0002-9394(62)92203-1/pdf|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|language=English|volume=54|issue=4|pages=717\u2013718|doi=10.1016/0002-9394(62)92203-1|pmid=13995745|issn=0002-9394}}</ref>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\n\n=== Death ===\nIn 1978, Walsh realized that he wasn't feeling very well and went to the doctor. A team at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital|Johns Hopkins]] diagnosed Walsh with oat cell carcinoma, which filled half of his lungs. He remained in Baltimore for about seven months up until his death in November 1978, at the age of 83.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== The Frank B. Walsh Neuro-Ophthalmalogy Society ===\nIn 1958, Frank Walsh and [[Richard Lindenberg]] started collaborating with the goal of forming a society where neuro-ophthalmologists could meet and discuss new ideas and facts. In 1966, Joel Sacks joined Walsh and Lindenberg, and the trio hosted their first meeting in 1969. The first three meetings, which they named the Neuro-Ophthalmic Pathology Symposium, included case presentations, clinical conferences, and discussion with local and visiting experts. These first meetings were small, but they were the first time that neuro-ophthalmologists from North America were able to meet as a group and collaborate. Over the years the society continued to grow, and it allowed experts to exchange information. As one member said, \"at the Walsh Society we saw and heard the cutting edge of neuro-ophthalmology, one or two years before it made the literature.\" After Walsh\u2019s death in 1978, the group was renamed as the Frank B. Walsh Neuro-Ophthalmology Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Knox|first=DL|date=December 1993|title=The History of the Frank B. Walsh Society|url=|journal=Journal of Clinical Neuro-ophthalmology|volume=13:4|pages=281\u2013287}}</ref>\n\nFor its first 23 years, the society had no formal organization, constitution, bylaws, dues, board of directors, or membership. Rather, it existed as a forum where experts of neurology and ophthalmology could casually collaborate and share experiences and findings. Even after 1990 when the society elected its first board of directors, was formally recognized as a not-for-profit entity by the state of Maryland, drafted a constitution and bylaws, and had a formal member list, the group saw themselves as a \"happy family\" rather than professionals meeting in a work environment. Some meetings were even described as \"raucous,\" with presentations being full of puns and clinical events so bizarre that the audience had no choice but to laugh.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1992, the Walsh Society became a subgroup of the North American Neuro-Ophthalmology Society. The integration of the Walsh Society into a larger, more official society, in addition to the creation of a board of directors, constitution, and formal membership, drew criticism from several members. Some believed that the movement to make the society more formal and organized turned a purely academic environment into one diluted by political and economic issues. The society still meets to this day on an annual basis.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Impact on Neuro-Ophthalmology ===\nIn the words of a modern neuro-ophthalmologist, \"Dr. Walsh developed a body of knowledge, recorded that knowledge, and shared it in an organized and systematic fashion which has not been improved upon, even to this day.\" <ref name=\":1\" /> In 2005, the sixth edition of ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' was published as ''Walsh and Hoyt's Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' in 3 volumes edited by [[Neil R. Miller]] and Nancy J. Newman.<ref name=\":5\">[http://www.eyecenter.emory.edu/faculty/newman.htm Nancy J. Newman, MD - Emory Eye Center - Emory University]</ref>\n\nAfter his death in 1978, the Wilmer Eye Institute established the Frank B. Walsh Chair of Neuro-ophthalmology, the first such chair in the world.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWalsh is considered by many to be the father of neuro-ophthalmology, as he both pioneered and promoted the field.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\n=== Postmortem honors ===\nIn 2000, Frank B. Walsh was inducted into the American Society of Cataract and Refractive Surgery Ophthalmology Hall of Fame.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Frank B.}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:American ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:People from Oxbow, Saskatchewan]]\n", "text_old": "{{tone|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Frank B. Walsh\n| image =\n| birth_date = October 18, 1895\n| birth_place = Oxbow, Saskatchewan, Canada\n| death_date = November 27, 1978\n| death_place = Baltimore, Maryland, United States of America\n| nationality = American-Canadian\n| education = Queen's University\nUniversity of Manitoba Medical School\n| occupation = Neuro-ophthalmologist\n}}\n\n'''Frank Burton Walsh''' (October 18, 1895, [[Oxbow, Saskatchewan]] \u2013 November 27, 1978, [[Baltimore, Maryland]]) was a Canadian-American ophthalmologist known for his work in [[neuro-ophthalmology]].<ref name=EyeWorldRef>{{cite journal|last1=Angelucci|first1=Diane|title=Groundbreaking neuro-ophthalmologist honored|journal=EyeWorld|date=February 2001|url=http://www.eyeworld.org/article.php?sid=1115}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[http://www.ascrs.org/honorees/frank-b-walsh-md Frank B. Walsh, MD | ASCRS]</ref> For the main duration of his career, Walsh worked as a neuro-ophthalmologist at the [[Wilmer Eye Institute|Wilmer Eye Institute of Johns Hopkins Hospital]]. Walsh is most well known for his textbook ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'', which contains a compilation of Walsh's case reports and the conclusions he drew from them. Originally published in 1947, the textbook has many updated versions and is still a premier text in the field of neuro-ophthalmology. Walsh is considered by many to be the father of neuro-ophthalmology due to his contributions to the field.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\">{{Cite journal|last=Udvarhelyi|first=George B.|date=1985-02-01|title=Frank B. Walsh M.D. The father of neuroophthalmology|journal=Surgical Neurology|language=English|volume=23|issue=2|pages=93\u201395|doi=10.1016/0090-3019(85)90325-8|issn=0090-3019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nFrank Burton Walsh was born in Oxbow, [[Saskatchewan]], Canada on October 18, 1895.  He comes from English-Irish descent. While he was in school, he participated in musical activities such as piano and clarinet. He also played sports, which included football, baseball and hockey. His other hobbies included hunting and fishing.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|url= |title=A personal sketch of Frank Burton Walsh |language=en|doi=10.1016/0039-6257(83)90179-0|volume=28|journal=Survey of Ophthalmology|pages=50\u201354 | last1 = Coston | first1 = Tullos O.|year=1983 }}</ref>\n[[File:Queen's University from the air 1919.jpg|thumb|Queen's University]]\nWalsh began his college education at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] (Canada) in 1913. During his time at Queen's, Walsh had to enlist for [[World War I]], where he became a lieutenant in the Canadian Army. Due to a wound at the [[Battle of Ypres]], he was sent home with an honorable discharge. He then went to the [[University of Manitoba College of Medicine]], where he received his medical degree in 1921.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhile working in private practice, Walsh started to gain interest in [[ophthalmology]]. Around this time, the Wilmer Institute of Ophthalmology in Baltimore, Maryland opened, so Walsh wrote to Dr. Wilmer asking for a resident position. Dr. Wilmer was extremely impressed with Walsh and granted him as a position as a first year resident. Walsh moved to Baltimore with his wife, Marion, and his two children, McMurty and Walter, in 1930 at the age of 35. By his fourth year, Walsh was the chief resident. He was almost 40 years old when he finished his residency.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMarion died in 1960 of a brain tumor, and Walsh remarried several years later to Josie. Josie worked as the head surgical nurse at the Winnipeg General Hospital.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early medical career ===\n[[File:Appendectomy at the French Hospital in Tiflis (Dartigues 1919).JPG|thumb|Example of an appendectomy]]\nFollowing Walsh's graduation from the [[University of Manitoba College of Medicine]] in 1921, he spent nine years in general practice.<ref name=\":1\" /> For the first two years, he was employed as a house officer at [[Winnipeg General Hospital]]. In 1923, Walsh moved to [[Estevan|Estavan, Saskatchewan]], where he delivered babies and performed [[Appendectomy|appendectomies]] as a general practitioner. In 1930 Walsh went back to school for ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\n=== Career in Neuro-Ophthalmology ===\nDuring Walsh's residency at the Wilmer Eye Institute, Walsh would see patients, teach, and host Saturday morning conferences that allowed ophthalmologists and neurologists to interact and discuss cases.<ref name=\":1\" /> Although Walsh worked in both [[neurology]] and [[ophthalmology]], he focused more on ophthalmology and was never formally a [[Neurology|neurologist]]. Walsh first entered the field of neuro-ophthalmology after approaching neuroscientist Dr. Frank Ford about performing joint research relating ophthalmology to the central nervous system during his last year of residency. Walsh's role in the research project included visiting many of Ford's patients and giving full ophthalmologic exams. Walsh then related his findings to many of the neurological findings of Ford. As Ford and Walsh's research project came to a close, Walsh realized he wanted to continue his studies in the relationship between neurology and ophthalmology. He published the ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' paper in 1936, which was the first research project in the field neuro-ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\nFollowing his residency, Walsh became a full-time staff member at the Wilmer Eye Institute of Johns Hopkins Hospital.<ref name=\":2\" /> Walsh left the Wilmer Eye Institute in 1945 to go into private practice in Baltimore, Maryland because of financial reasons.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWalsh is most well known for coauthoring ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' in 1947'','' which is the first textbook on neuro-ophthalmology. The book contained years of Walsh's observations, analysis, and cataloguing of diseases that affect the eye through the nervous system.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1960s, there were only 4 neuro-ophthalmologists in the United States. Over the course of Walsh's career, the number of neuro-ophthalmologists greatly increased, and many in the field looked to Walsh's work for their education and training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://professorships.jhu.edu/professorship/frank-b-walsh-professorship-neuro-ophthalmology/|title=Frank B. Walsh Professorship in Neuro-Ophthalmology - Named Deanships, Directorships, and Professorships|work=Named Deanships, Directorships, and Professorships|access-date=2017-04-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, following the death of his wife, Walsh returned as a full-time faculty member at Wilmer, where he remained until his death in 1978.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Research ===\n[[File:Medical instrument Eye Retinoscope.jpg|thumb|An example of a Retinoscope, one of the tools Walsh used to diagnose visual syndromes.]]\nWalsh's contributions to neuro-ophthalmology extended beyond his clinical work and teachings. Walsh documented and analyzed all of his clinical cases, and used them to perform research. He wrote down many of his major discoveries in published research papers. One of his most cited papers was on Tilted Disk Syndrome.<ref>{{Cite journal|url= |title=The Tilted Disk Syndrome  |doi=10.1016/0002-9394(76)90658-9|pmid=937453 |volume=82|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|pages=16\u201323 | last1 = Ellen Young | first1 = Sue|year=1976 }}</ref> He used many techniques, such as [[Retinoscopy]], Static and Kinetic Golmann Perimetry, [[Fluorescein angiography]], and ocular ultrasonography, to diagnose the syndrome. Walsh discovered several symptoms that could be used as diagnostic tools, such as an obliquely direct axis of the vertical disk.\n\nIn another one of his most cited articles, Walsh discussed whether [[oral contraceptives]] affected or complicated the parts of a patient's brain related to the eyes. Walsh came to the conclusion that, while birth control pills may cause hazards to visions in some extreme cases due to blood clotting, they did not normally cause problems with vision.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WALSH|first=F. B.|last2=CLARK|first2=D. B.|last3=THOMPSON|first3=R. S.|last4=NICHOLSON|first4=D. H.|date=1965-11-01|title=Oral Contraceptives and Neuro-Ophthalmologic Interest|url=http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamaophthalmology/fullarticle/628190|journal=Archives of Ophthalmology|language=en|volume=74|issue=5|pages=628\u2013640|doi=10.1001/archopht.1965.00970040630009|pmid=5321209|issn=0003-9950}}</ref>\n\n=== Accomplishments and honors ===\nWalsh received the following awards over his career:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* Lucian Howe Medal from [[American Ophthalmological Society]]\n* Jules Stein Award from the Jules Stein Institute at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n* Proctor Award from [[American Medical Association]] \n* Karl-Leibrecht Prize from German Ophthalmological Society\n* Proctor Medical Award from Association for Research in Ophthalmology\nIn addition to receiving these awards, Walsh also held positions within these groups:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* President and Member of the Board of Scientific Counselors at [[National Institutes of Health]]\n* President of the [[American Ophthalmological Society]] \n* Vice President of [[American Academy of Ophthalmology|American Academy of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology]]\n* Second Vice President of [[American Medical Association]] \nWalsh was also inducted as an honorary member in these Neurological and Ophthalmological societies:<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n* American Neurological Society\n* [[American Association of Neurological Surgeons]]\n* Canadian Ophthalmological Society\n* Australian Ophthalmological Society\n* German Ophthalmological Society\n* Irish Ophthalmological Society\n* Brazilian Ophthalmological Society\n* Sicilian Ophthalmological Society\n* Columbian Ophthalmological Society\n* Mexican Ophthalmological Society\n* Peruvian Ophthalmological Society\n* Uruguayan Ophthalmological Society\nWalsh received honorary Doctor  of Science degrees from the University of Western Australia and the University of Manitoba, and honorary Doctor of Law degrees from Queen's University and the Johns Hopkins University.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the October 1962 issue of the ''[[American Journal of Ophthalmology]]'', there was a special article about Walsh himself. In the article, Walsh is depicted as the leader of the field of neuro-ophthalmology.<ref name=\"Vail 717\u2013718\">{{Cite journal|last=Vail|first=Derrick|date=1962-10-01|title=Frank Burton Walsh, M.D.|url=http://www.ajo.com/article/0002-9394(62)92203-1/pdf|journal=American Journal of Ophthalmology|language=English|volume=54|issue=4|pages=717\u2013718|doi=10.1016/0002-9394(62)92203-1|pmid=13995745|issn=0002-9394}}</ref>\n\n== Death and legacy ==\n\n=== Death ===\nIn 1978, Walsh realized that he wasn't feeling very well and went to the doctor. A team at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital|Johns Hopkins]] diagnosed Walsh with oat cell carcinoma, which filled half of his lungs. He remained in Baltimore for about seven months up until his death in November 1978, at the age of 83.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== The Frank B. Walsh Neuro-Ophthalmalogy Society ===\nIn 1958, Frank Walsh and [[Richard Lindenberg]] started collaborating with the goal of forming a society where neuro-ophthalmologists could meet and discuss new ideas and facts. In 1966, Joel Sacks joined Walsh and Lindenberg, and the trio hosted their first meeting in 1969. The first three meetings, which they named the Neuro-Ophthalmic Pathology Symposium, included case presentations, clinical conferences, and discussion with local and visiting experts. These first meetings were small, but they were the first time that neuro-ophthalmologists from North America were able to meet as a group and collaborate. Over the years the society continued to grow, and it allowed experts to exchange information. As one member said, \"at the Walsh Society we saw and heard the cutting edge of neuro-ophthalmology, one or two years before it made the literature.\" After Walsh\u2019s death in 1978, the group was renamed as the Frank B. Walsh Neuro-Ophthalmology Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Knox|first=DL|date=December 1993|title=The History of the Frank B. Walsh Society|url=|journal=Journal of Clinical Neuro-ophthalmology|volume=13:4|pages=281\u2013287}}</ref>\n\nFor its first 23 years, the society had no formal organization, constitution, bylaws, dues, board of directors, or membership. Rather, it existed as a forum where experts of neurology and ophthalmology could casually collaborate and share experiences and findings. Even after 1990 when the society elected its first board of directors, was formally recognized as a not-for-profit entity by the state of Maryland, drafted a constitution and bylaws, and had a formal member list, the group saw themselves as a \"happy family\" rather than professionals meeting in a work environment. Some meetings were even described as \"raucous,\" with presentations being full of puns and clinical events so bizarre that the audience had no choice but to laugh.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1992, the Walsh Society became a subgroup of the North American Neuro-Ophthalmology Society. The integration of the Walsh Society into a larger, more official society, in addition to the creation of a board of directors, constitution, and formal membership, drew criticism from several members. Some believed that the movement to make the society more formal and organized turned a purely academic environment into one diluted by political and economic issues. The society still meets to this day on an annual basis.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Impact on Neuro-Ophthalmology ===\nIn the words of a modern neuro-ophthalmologist, \"Dr. Walsh developed a body of knowledge, recorded that knowledge, and shared it in an organized and systematic fashion which has not been improved upon, even to this day.\" <ref name=\":1\" /> In 2005, the sixth edition of ''Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' was published as ''Walsh and Hoyt's Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology'' in 3 volumes edited by [[Neil R. Miller]] and Nancy J. Newman.<ref name=\":5\">[http://www.eyecenter.emory.edu/faculty/newman.htm Nancy J. Newman, MD - Emory Eye Center - Emory University]</ref>\n\nAfter his death in 1978, the Wilmer Eye Institute established the Frank B. Walsh Chair of Neuro-ophthalmology, the first such chair in the world.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWalsh is considered by many to be the father of neuro-ophthalmology, as he both pioneered and promoted the field.<ref name=\"Udvarhelyi 93\u201395\" />\n\n=== Postmortem honors ===\nIn 2000, Frank B. Walsh was inducted into the American Society of Cataract and Refractive Surgery Ophthalmology Hall of Fame.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Frank B.}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:American ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:People from Oxbow, Saskatchewan]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_B._Walsh"}
{"title_page": "Lhasa (prefecture-level city)", "text_new": "{{About|the prefecture-level city and city proper|the inner urban area|Lhasa|other uses|Lhasa (disambiguation)}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Lhasa\n|official_name          = \n|native_name            = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|zh-Hans|\u62c9\u8428\u5e02}}}}<br/>{{lang|bo|\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f41\u0fb1\u0f7a\u0f62\u0f0d}}}}\n|settlement_type        = [[Prefecture-level city]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = Collage of views of Lhasa, Tibet.jpg\n|image_caption          = '''From upper left''': roof of the [[Jokhang]] Temple; [[Norbulingka]] monastery main gate; [[Potala Palace]]; [[Dharmacakra|Wheel of Dharma]] and [[Tibetan prayer wheel|prayer wheels]] (bottom), Jokhang; satellite picture of Lhasa\n|image_map              = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=shape|stroke-width=2|stroke-color=#000000|zoom=7|frame-lat=30.13|frame-long=91.11}}\n|image_map1             = Location of Lhasa within Xizang (China).png\n|imagesize              = 250\n|mapsize1               = 250\n|map_caption1           = Location of Lhasa prefecture-level city jurisdiction in the Tibet Autonomous Region\n|image_map2             = Lhasa municipality relief map png.png\n|mapsize2               = 250\n|map_caption2           = Relief map of Lhasa\n|image_dot_map          = \n|dot_mapsize            = \n|dot_map_caption        = \n|dot_x                  = \n|dot_y                  = \n|pushpin_map            = \n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Autonomous regions of China|Autonomous region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]]\n|government_footnotes   = \n|government_type        = [[Prefecture-level city]]\n|leader_title           = [[Party Committee Secretary|Party Secretary]]\n|leader_name            = [[Che Dalha]]\n|leader_title1          = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name1           = [[Zhang Tingqing]]\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n|established_title2     = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     = <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date3      = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref              = \n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         = 29274\n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban_km2         = 53\n|area_metro_km2         = \n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2015\n|population_footnotes           = \n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 902500<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lasa.gov.cn/lasa/lsrk/column_common.shtml |title = \u62c9\u8428\u4eba\u53e3}}</ref>\n|population_urban               = \n|population_density_km2         = 30.8\n|population_density_sq_mi       = \n|population_blank1_title        = \n|population_blank1              = \n|population_density_blank1_km2  = \n|population_blank2_title        = \n|population_blank2              = \n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Time in China|China Standard]]\n|utc_offset             = +8\n|coordinates            = {{Coord|29|39|N|91|07|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-54|display=it}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 4200\n<!-- Area/postal codes and others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = [[List of postal codes in China|Postal code]]\n|postal_code            = \n|area_code              = 891\n|website                = [http://www.lasa.gov.cn/ Lasa.gov.cn]\n|blank_name             = [[Vehicle registration plates of China|Licence plate prefixes]]\n|blank_info             = {{lang|zh-cn|\u85cfA}}\n|iso_code               = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-XZ-01]]\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n  |pic=File:Lhasa-dz-zh.svg\n  |piccap=\"Lhasa\" in [[Simplified Chinese characters]] (left) and [[Tibetan script]] (right)\n  |s={{linktext|\u62c9\u8428}}\n  |t={{linktext|\u62c9\u85a9}}\n  |p=L\u0101s\u00e0\n  |bpmf=\u310c\u311a&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3119\u311a\u02cb\n  |gr=Lhasah\n  |w=La<sup>1</sup>-sa<sup>4</sup>\n  |mi={{IPAc-cmn|l|a|1|.|s|a|4}}\n  |l=(Tibetan) \"Place of the Gods\"\n  |altname=Also known as\n  |s2={{linktext|\u903b\u4e9b}}\n  |t2={{linktext|\u908f\u4e9b}}\n  |p2=Lu\u00f3xi\u0113\n  |bpmf2=\u310c\u3128\u311b\u02ca&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3112\u3127\u311d\n  |gr2=Luoshie\n  |w2=Lo<sup>2</sup>-hsieh<sup>1</sup>\n  |mi2={{IPAc-cmn|l|uo|2|.|x|ie|1}}\n  |showflag=p\n  |tib={{bo-textonly|\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b}}\n    |wylie=lha sa\n    |thdl=Lhasa\n    |zwpy=Lhasa\n    |lhasa={{IPA|[l\u0325\u00e1s\u0259]}} or {{IPA|[l\u0325\u025c\u0301\u02d0s\u0259]}}\n  |order=st\n}}\n\n'''Lhasa'''{{efn|The term ''Lasa City'' ({{lang|zh-hans|\u62c9\u8428\u5e02}}) literally means \"Lhasa City\" or \"Lhasa Municipality\". It is at the same level as a prefecture for administrative purposes. It contains the [[Lhasa|Chengguan District]], [[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]], [[Dagz\u00ea District]], and other rural areas.{{sfn|Barnett|1996|p=82}}}} ({{zh|s=\u62c9\u8428\u5e02|t=\u62c9\u85a9\u5e02|p=L\u0101s\u00e0 Sh\u00ec}}) is a [[prefecture-level city]], one of the main administrative divisions of the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]] of [[China]]. It covers an area of {{convert|29274|km2}} of rugged and sparsely populated terrain. Its capital and largest city is [[Lhasa]], with around 300,000 residents, which mostly corresponds with the administrative Chengguan District, while its suburbs extend into [[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]] and [[Dagz\u00ea District]]. The consolidated prefecture-level city contains additional five, mostly rural, counties.\n\nThe city boundaries roughly correspond to the basin of the [[Lhasa River]], a major tributary of the [[Yarlung Tsangpo|Yarlung Tsangpo River]]. It lies on the [[Lhasa terrane]], the last unit of crust to accrete to the Eurasian plate before the continent of India collided with Asia about 50 million years ago and pushed up the [[Himalayas]]. The terrane is high, contains a complex pattern of faults and is tectonically active. The temperature is generally warm in summer and rises above freezing on sunny days in winter. Most of the rain falls in summer. The upland areas and northern grasslands are used for grazing yaks, sheep and goats, while the river valleys support agriculture with crops such as barley, wheat and vegetables. Wildlife is not abundant, but includes the rare [[snow leopard]] and [[black-necked crane]]. Mining has caused some environmental problems.\n\nThe 2000 census gave a total population of 474,490, of whom 387,124 were ethnic Tibetans. The Han Chinese population at the time was mainly concentrated in urban areas. The prefecture-level city is traversed by two major highways and by the [[Qinghai\u2013Tibet railway]], which terminates in the city of Lhasa. Two large dams on the Lhasa River deliver hydroelectric power, as do many smaller dams and the [[Yangbajain Geothermal Station|Yangbajain Geothermal Field]]. The population is well-served by primary schools and basic medical facilities, although more advanced facilities are lacking. [[Tibetan Buddhism]] and monastic life have been dominant aspects of the local culture since the 7th century. Most of the monasteries were destroyed during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but since then many have been restored and serve as tourist attractions.\n\n==Geography==\n===Location===\nLhasa lies in south-central Tibet, to the north of the Himalayas.\nThe prefecture-level city is {{convert|277|km}} from east to west and {{convert|202|km}} from north to south. It covers an area of {{convert|29518|km2}}.{{sfn|Lhasa, Baidu Baike}}\nIt is bordered by [[Nagqu]] City to the north, [[Nyingchi]] City to the east, [[Shannan, Tibet|Shannan]]/Lhoka City to the south and [[Shigatse|Xigaz\u00ea]] City to the west.{{sfn|Tibet Maps, ChinaTourGuide}}\nThe prefecture-level city roughly corresponds to the basin of the [[Lhasa River]], which is the center of Tibet politically, economically and culturally.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=151}} Chengguan District is also the center of Tibet in terms of transport, communications, education and religion, as well as being the most developed part of Tibet and a major tourist destination with sights such as the [[Potala Palace]], [[Jokhang]] and [[Ramoche Temple]].{{sfn|Chengguan District of Lhasa, Baidu Baike}}\n\n===Lhasa River basin===\n[[File:Tibet-6080 (2695594944).jpg|thumb|[[Lhasa River]] to the south of [[Lhasa]]]]\n\nLhasa prefecture-level city roughly corresponds to the basin of the [[Lhasa River]], a major tributary of the [[Yarlung Tsangpo River]]. Exceptions are the north of [[Damxung County]], which crosses the watershed of the [[Nyenchen Tanglha Mountains]] and includes part of the [[Namtso]] lake,{{sfn|Damxung, Baidu Baike}}{{efn|Namtso lake is the second-largest salt lake in China. It has vivid turquoise-blue waters and is set in spectacular scenery. The Tashi Dor Monastery is at an elevation of {{convert|4718|m}} in the southeastern corner of the lake.{{sfn|Chow|Eimer|Heller|Huhti|2009|p=928}} }} and [[Ny\u00eamo County]], which covers the basin of the [[Nimu Maqu River]], a direct tributary of the Yarlung Tsangpo.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County, Baidu Baike}}\nThe river basin is separated from the Yarlung Tsangpo valley to the south by the [[Goikarla Rigyu]] range.{{sfn|Tibet, chinamaps.org}}\nThe largest tributary of the [[Lhasa River]], the [[Reting Tsangpo]], originates in the Chenthangula Mountains in Nagqu Prefecture at an elevation of about {{convert|5500|m}}, and flows southwest into Lhasa past [[Reting Monastery]].{{sfn|Winn|2015}}\n\nThe [[Lhasa River]] drains an area of {{convert|32471|km2}}, and is the largest tributary of the middle section of the Yarlung Tsangpo. \nThe average altitude of the basin is around {{convert|4500|m}}.\nThe basin has complex geology and is tectonically active. Earthquakes are common.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=151}}\nAnnual runoff is {{convert|10550000000|m3}}. \nWater quality is good, with little discharge of sewage and minimal chemical pesticides and fertilizers.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=152}}\n\nThe Lhasa River forms where three smaller rivers converge.\nThese are the Phak Chu, the Phongdolha Chu which flows from [[Damxung County]] and the [[Reting Tsangpo]], which rises beyond the [[Reting Monastery]].{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=125}}\nThe highest tributary rises at around {{convert|5290|m}} on the southern slope of the [[Nyenchen Tanglha Mountains]].{{sfn|Ortlam|1991|pp=385\u2013399}}\nIn its upper reaches the river flows southeast through a deep valley.{{sfn|\u0414\u0436\u0438\u0447\u0443, \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f}}\nLower down the river valley is flatter and changes its direction to the southwest, The river expands to a width of {{convert|150|to|200|m}}.{{sfn|\u0414\u0436\u0438\u0447\u0443, \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f}}\nMajor tributaries in the lower reaches include the [[Pengbo River]] and the [[Duilong River]].{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=153}}\nAt its mouth the Lhasa Valley is about {{convert|3|mi}} wide.{{sfn|Waddell|1905|p=317}}\n\nThe bulk of the water is supplied by the summer monsoon rains, which fall from July to September.\nThere are floods in the summer from July to September, with about 17% of the annual runoff flowing in September.\nIn winter the river has low water, and sometimes freezes. \nTotal flow is about {{convert|4|km3}}, with average flow about {{convert|125|m3/s}}.{{sfn|\u0414\u0436\u0438\u0447\u0443, \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f}}\nThe total hydropower potential of the river basin is 2,560,000&nbsp;kW.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=152}}\n[[Zhikong Hydro Power Station]] in [[Maizhokunggar County]] delivers 100&nbsp;MW.{{sfn|Zheng|2007}}\nThe [[Pangduo Hydro Power Station]] in [[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]] has total installed capacity of 160 MW.{{sfn|Guan|2013}}\n\n==Geology==\nThe former Lhasa prefecture lies in the [[Lhasa terrane]], to which it gives its name. This is thought to be the last crustal block to [[Accretion (geology)|accrete]] to the Eurasian plate before the collision with the Indian plate in the Cenozoic.{{sfn|Zhang|Dong|Santosh|Zhao|2014|p=170\u2013171}}\nThe terrane is separated from the [[Himalayas]] to the south by the [[Yarlung-Tsangpo suture]], and from the [[Qiangtang terrane]] to the north by the [[Bangong-Nujiang suture]].{{sfn|Ozacar|2015}}\nThe Lhasa terrane consisted of two blocks before the [[Mesozoic]], the North Lhasa Block and the South Lhasa Block.{{sfn|Wan|2010|p=139}}\nThese blocks were joined in the Late Paleozoic.{{sfn|Zhang|Dong|Santosh|Zhao|2014|p=170\u2013171}}\n\n[[File:Lhasa terrane approach to Qiangtang terrane.svg|thumb|300px|[[Lhasa terrane]] approach to Qiangtang terrane]]\nThe Lhasa terrane moved northward and collided with the Qiangtang terrane along the [[Bangong suture]].{{sfn|Wan|2010|p=210}}{{sfn|Metcalfe|1994|pp=97\u2013111}}\nThe collision began towards the end of the late [[Jurassic]] ({{circa|163\u2013145}} Ma{{efn|Ma \u2013 Million years ago}}), and collision activity continued until the early [[Late Cretaceous]] ({{circa|100\u201366}} Ma). \nDuring this period the terrane may have been shortened by at least {{convert|180|km}}.{{sfn|Ozacar|2015}}\nThe collision caused a peripheral [[foreland basin]] to form in the north part of the Lhasa terrane. \nIn some parts of the foreland basin the north-dipping [[subduction]] of the Neotethyan oceanic crust below the Lhasa terrane caused volcanism. \nThe [[Gangdese batholith]] was formed as this subduction continued along the southern margin of the Lhasa terrane.{{sfn|Leier|Kapp|Gehrels|DeCelles|2007|p=363}}\nThe Gangdese intrudes the southern half of the Lhasa terrain.{{sfn|Alsdorf|BrownNelson|Makovsky|1998|p=502}}\n\nContact with India began along the Yarlung-Zangbo suture around 50 Ma during the [[Eocene]], and the two continents continue to converge. \nMagmatism continued in the Gangdese arc until as late as 40 Ma.{{sfn|Alsdorf|BrownNelson|Makovsky|1998|p=502}}\nThere was significant crustal shortening as the collision progressed.{{sfn|Liebke|Appel|Ding|Neumann|2010|p=1199}}\nThe South Lhasa terrane experienced metamorphism and magmatism in the Early Cenozoic (55\u201345 Ma) and metamorphism in the Late Eocene (40\u201330 Ma), presumably due to the collision between the continents of India and Eurasia.{{sfn|Zhang|Dong|Santosh|Zhao|2014|p=170\u2013171}}\n\nRocks in this region include sedimentary rocks from the [[Paleozoic]] and [[Mesozoic]] into which granite has intruded during the [[Cretaceous]].\nThe rocks have metamorphosed and are deeply eroded and faulted.{{sfn|Winn|2015}}\nThe rocks exposed in the [[Reting Tsangpo]] canyon range in age from 400&nbsp;Ma to 50&nbsp;Ma.\nThe result of faulting has been to often juxtapose relatively recent rocks with much older rocks.\nSome parts of the ocean floor were pushed up onto the [[Tibetan Plateau]] and formed marble or slate.\nSea fossils from 400&nbsp;Ma are found in the river's canyons, and houses are roofed with slate.{{sfn|Winn|2015}}\n\nThe Yangbajing Basin lies between the [[Nyainquentanglha Range]] to the northwest and the Yarlu-Zangbo suture to the south.{{sfn|Dor|Zhao|2000|p=1084}}\nThe [[Yangbajain Geothermal Field]] is in the central part of a [[half-graben]] fault-depression basin caused by the foremontane fault zone of the Nyainqentanglha Mountains.{{sfn|Shen|1996|p=50}}\nThe SE-dipping detachment fault began to form about 8&nbsp;Ma.{{sfn|Harrison|2006|p=214}}\nThe geothermal reservoir is basically a Quaternary basin underlaid by a large granite [[batholith]].\nThe basin has been filled with glacial deposits from the north and alluvial-pluvial sediments from the south.\nFluid flows horizontally into the reservoir through the faults around the basin.{{sfn|Shen|1996|p=50}}\nChemical analysis of the thermal fluid indicate that there is shallow-seated magmatic activity not far below the geothermal field.{{sfn|Shen|1996|p=17}}\n\nDuring the [[ice age]]s of the last two million years the Tibetan plateau and the Himalayas have been covered by the expanded [[polar ice cap]] several times. As the ice moved it eroded the rock, filling the river canyons with gravel. In some sections the rivers have cut through the gravel and flow swiftly over bedrock, and in some areas large boulders have fallen into the rivers and formed rapids.{{sfn|Winn|2015}}\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean County1.jpg|thumb|Pasturage in Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]]\nThe Lhasa valley is roughly the same latitude as the southern United States, but at an altitude of {{convert|3610|m}} or more it is of course cooler.{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=126}}\nThe central river valleys of Tibet are warm in summer, and even in the coldest months of winter the temperature is above freezing on sunny days.{{sfn|Kapstein|2013|p=7}}\nThe climate is semi-arid monsoon, with a low average temperature of {{convert|1.2|to|7.5|\u00b0C}}. \nAverage annual precipitation is {{convert|466.3|mm}}, with 85% falling in the June\u2013September period.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=151}}\nTypically there are 3,000 hours of sunshine each year.{{sfn|Lhasa, Baidu Baike}}\nIt is cooler in the northern regions, warmer in the south. Annual figures:\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|District !!rowspan=2|Region !!colspan=2|Average temperature !!rowspan=2|Frost-free<br/> days !! colspan=2|Precipitation\n|-\n!\u00b0C !! \u00b0F !!mm !!in\n|-\n|[[Chengguan District, Lhasa|Chengguan District]]{{sfn|Chengguan District of Lhasa, Baidu Baike}} || Central \n|style=\"text-align:center\"|8\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 46\u00b0||style=\"text-align:center\"| 110 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 500 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 20\n|-\n|[[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]]{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}{{sfn|Ge Le|Li Tao|1996|p=35}} || Central \n|style=\"text-align:center\"| 7\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|45\u00b0 || style=\"text-align:center\"|120 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 310 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|12\n|-\n|[[Dagz\u00ea District]]{{sfn|Basic Dazi|, DIIB}} || Central \n|style=\"text-align:center\"|7.5\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|45.5\u00b0||style=\"text-align:center\"| 130 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 500||style=\"text-align:center\"|20\n|-\n|[[Damxung County]]{{sfn|Mei|2008}} || North \n|style=\"text-align:center\"| 1.3\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|34.3\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 62 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|481 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|18.9\n|-\n|[[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]] {{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}} || Central\n|style=\"text-align:center\"| 2.9\u20135.8\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|37.2\u201342.4\u00b0 || style=\"text-align:center\"|120 || style=\"text-align:center\"|310 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|12\n|-\n|[[Maizhokunggar County]]{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, TibetOL}} || Central \n|style=\"text-align:center\"|5.1\u20139.1\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|41.2\u201348.4\u00b0 || style=\"text-align:center\"|90 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 515.9 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|20.31\n|-\n|[[Ny\u00eamo County]]{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County, Baidu Baike}} || South\n|style=\"text-align:center\"| 6.7\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|44.1\u00b0 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 100 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 324.2 ||style=\"text-align:center\"|12.76\n|-\n|[[Q\u00fcx\u00fc County]]{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, CGN}} || South \n|style=\"text-align:center\"| ||style=\"text-align:center\"| ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 150 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 441.9 ||style=\"text-align:center\"| 17.40\n|}\nStudies of temperature and precipitation data from 1979 to 2005 indicate that higher temperatures are leading to longer snow-free periods at the lower elevations. \nHowever, at higher levels the amount of precipitation has increased, so despite warming the snow-free period is shorter.{{sfn|J. Gao|2013|p=594}}\n\n==Environment==\n[[File:Black Necked Cranes.jpg|thumb|[[Black-necked crane]]s]]\nMost of the population of Tibet lives in the southern valleys, including those around Lhasa.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=138}}\nThe higher regions are used by nomadic ''drokpa'' who tend herds of yaks, sheep and goats on the steppe grasslands of the hills and high valleys.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=138}}{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=126}}\nIn the lower parts it is possible to cultivate products that include barley, wheat, black peas, beans, mustard, hemp, potatoes, cabbage, cauliflower, onions, garlic, celery and tomatoes. The traditional staple food is barley flour called ''[[tsampa]]'', often combined with buttered tea and made into a paste.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=138}}\n\nA visitor described the valley around Lhasa in 1889 as follows,\n{{blockquote|The plain over which we are riding is a wonderfully fruitful one. It is skirted on the south by the Kyi{{efn|The Kyi River is another name for the Lhasa River}} river, and is watered, moreover, by another smaller stream from the north, which flows into the Kyi ... some five miles west of Lhasa. All this land is carefully irrigated by means of dikes and cross-channels from both rivers. Fields of buckwheat, barley, pea, rape, and lindseed lie in orderly series everywhere. The meadows near the water display the richest emerald-green pasturage. Groves of poplar and willow, in shapely clumps, combine with the grassy stretches to give in places a parklike appearance to the scene. Several hamlets and villages, such as Cheri, Daru, and Shing Dongkhar, are dotted over these lands. A fertile plain truly for a besieging army!{{sfn|Sandberg|1889|p=707}} }}\n\n[[File:Bharal, Himalayan blue sheep.jpg|thumb|[[Bharal]]. [[Snow leopard]]s are one of the main predators of this sheep.{{sfn|Huffman|2004}}]]\nThe Lhasa region does not have abundant wildlife or great numbers of species, but the Lhasa valley does support wintering populations of hundreds of [[black-necked crane]]s.{{sfn|Bisht|2008|p=73}}\n[[Hutoushan Reservoir]] lies in Qangka Township, Lh\u00fcnzhub County.\nThe reservoir is bordered by large swamps and wet meadows, and has abundant plants and shellfish.{{sfn|Lhasa, Tibet Linzhou Hutoushan reservoir is a paradise...}}\nThe reservoir, which lies in the Pengbo valley, is the largest in Tibet, with total storage of {{convert|12000000|m3}}.{{sfn|Shen|1995|p=153}}\nEndangered black-necked cranes migrate to the middle and southern part of Tibet every winter, and may be seen on the reservoir and elsewhere in the Lhasa region.{{sfn|Lin|2013}}\nOther wildlife includes [[bharal]], [[pheasant]]s, [[roe deer]], [[Thorold's deer]], [[Mongolian gazelle]], [[Siberian ibex]], [[otter]], [[brown bear]], [[snow leopard]] and [[duck]].{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, Lhasa Tourism}}{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nMedicinal plants include fritillaries (''[[fritillaria]]''), stonecrop (''[[rhodiola]]''), Indian barberry (''[[berberis aristata]]''), Chinese caterpillar fungus (''[[ophiocordyceps sinensis]]''), ''[[codonopsis]]'' and [[Lingzhi mushroom]] (''ganoderma'').{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, Lhasa Tourism}}{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\n\nThe dams on the Lhasa river built as part of the Three Rivers Development Project are unlikely to affect the flow of the Brahmaputra in India.{{sfn|Chellaney|2013|p=158}}\nHowever, the climate and soil are unsuitable for large-scale irrigation.\nWhere grasslands have been converted into irrigated farms fed by dams the result may damage the environment.{{sfn|Chellaney|2013|p=160}}\nJama wetland in [[Maizhokunggar County]] is vulnerable to grazing and climate change.{{sfn|Bai|Shang|Zhang|2012|p=1761}}\nExtensive mining in some mountainous regions have turned areas of what was green pasturage into a grey wasteland. \nThe authorities are reported to have suppressed protests by the local people.{{sfn|Tibetans rebuked for protesting ... 2012}}\nMilitary personnel have been involved in efforts to protect and improve the environment, including replanting programs.{{sfn|Guo|2014}}\n\nA 2015 study reported that during the non-monsoon season the levels of [[arsenic]] in the [[Duilong River]], at 205.6 \u03bcg/L were higher than the [[WHO]] guideline of 10 \u03bcg/L for drinking water.{{sfn|Li|Kang|Chen|Zhang|2013|p=4143}}\nThe source of the pollution seems to be untreated water from the [[Yangbajain Geothermal Field]] power station.\nIt can be detected {{convert|90|km}} downstream from this site.{{sfn|Zhang|Huang|1997}}\n\n==Administrative divisions==\nLhasa prefecture-level city consists of three [[District (China)|district]]s and five [[Counties of the People's Republic of China|counties]]. \nChengguan District, Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District, and Dagz\u00ea District contains most of the urban area of Lhasa, which lies in the Lhasa River valley floor.\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n! colspan=\"8\" | Map\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" | <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Lhasa.png|width=600|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=700|y=890|scale=600/1580|text=[[Chengguan District, Lhasa|<span style=\"font-size:smaller\">'''Chengguan'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=450|y=850|scale=600/1580|text=[[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District|'''Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=890|y=860|scale=600/1580|text=[[Dagz\u00ea District|'''Dagz\u00ea'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=510|y=440|scale=600/1580|text=[[Damxung County|'''Damxung<br>County'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=480|y=990|scale=600/1580|text=[[Q\u00fcx\u00fc County|'''Q\u00fcx\u00fc<br>County'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=130|y=930|scale=600/1580|text=[[Ny\u00eamo County|'''Ny\u00eamo<br>County'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=810|y=590|scale=600/1580|text=[[Lh\u00fcnzhub County|'''Lh\u00fcnzhub<br>County'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=1090|y=760|scale=600/1580|text=[[Maizhokunggar County|'''Maizhokunggar<br>County'''</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=710|y=950|scale=600/1580|text=[[Liuwu Subdistrict|{{small|'''''Liuwu'''''}}</span>]]}}\n{{Image label|x=540|y=180|scale=600/1580|text=[[Namtso|''Lake<br>Nam''</span>]]}}\n</div>\n|-\n! Name\n! Chinese\n! Hanyu Pinyin\n! [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]]\n! [[Wylie transliteration|Wylie]]<br>[[Tibetan pinyin]]\n! Population (2010)\n! Area {{small|(km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n! Density {{small|(/km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"8\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''City Proper'''\n|-\n|[[Chengguan District, Lhasa|Chengguan District]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u57ce\u5173\u533a}}||{{transl|zh|Ch\u00e9nggu\u0101n Q\u016b}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f41\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f40\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|khrin kon chus|lang=no}}<br>{{transl|bo|Chingoin Q\u00fc|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|279,074 ||style=\"text-align:right\"|525||style=\"text-align:right\"|531.56\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"8\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''Suburban'''\n|-\n|[[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u5806\u9f99\u5fb7\u5e86\u533a}}||{{transl|zh|Du\u012bl\u00f3ngd\u00e9q\u00ecng Q\u016b}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|stod lung bde chen chus}}<br>{{transl|bo|D\u00f6lungd\u00eaq\u00ean Q\u00fc|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|52,249||style=\"text-align:right\"|2,672||style=\"text-align:right\"|19.55\n|-\n|[[Dagz\u00ea District]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u8fbe\u5b5c\u533a}}||{{transl|zh|D\u00e1z\u012b Q\u016b}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fa9\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|stag rtse chus}}<br>{{transl|bo|Dagz\u00ea Q\u00fc|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|26,708||style=\"text-align:right\"|1,361||style=\"text-align:right\"|19.62\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"8\"  style=\"text-align:center; \"| '''Rural'''\n|-\n|[[Damxung County]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u5f53\u96c4\u53bf}}||{{transl|zh|D\u0101ngxi\u00f3ng Xi\u00e0n}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f60\u0f51\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fab\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|dam gzhung rdzong}}<br>{{transl|bo|Damxung Zong|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|46,463||style=\"text-align:right\"|10,234||style=\"text-align:right\"|4.54\n|-\n|[[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u6797\u5468\u53bf}}||{{transl|zh|L\u00ednzh\u014du Xi\u00e0n}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f74\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fab\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|lhun grub rdzong}}<br>{{transl|bo|Lh\u00fcnzhub Zong|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|50,246||style=\"text-align:right\"|4,100||style=\"text-align:right\"|12.25\n|-\n|[[Maizhokunggar County]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u58a8\u7af9\u5de5\u5361\u53bf}}||{{transl|zh|M\u00f2zh\u00fag\u014dngk\u01ce Xi\u00e0n}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f58\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f40\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fab\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|mal gro gung dkar rdzong}}<br>{{transl|bo|Maizhokunggar Zong|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|44,674||style=\"text-align:right\"|5,492||style=\"text-align:right\"|8.13\n|-\n|[[Ny\u00eamo County]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u5c3c\u6728\u53bf}}||{{transl|zh|N\u00edm\u00f9 Xi\u00e0n}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f66\u0f99\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fab\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|snye mo rdzong}}<br>{{transl|bo|Ny\u00eamo Zong|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|28,149||style=\"text-align:right\"|3,266||style=\"text-align:right\"|8.61\n|-\n|[[Q\u00fcx\u00fc County]]||{{lang|zh-hans|\u66f2\u6c34\u53bf}}||{{transl|zh|Q\u016bshu\u01d0 Xi\u00e0n}}||{{bo-textonly|\u0f46\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f64\u0f74\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fab\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b}}||{{transl|bo|chu shur rdzong}}<br>{{transl|bo|Q\u00fcx\u00fc Zong|lang=no}}||style=\"text-align:right\"|31,860||style=\"text-align:right\"|1,624||style=\"text-align:right\"|19.61\n|}\n\n===Chengguan District===\n[[File:\u5e03\u8fbe\u62c9\u5bab.jpg|thumb|The [[Potala Palace]] to the west of the old city, now surrounded by recent buildings]]\n[[File:049 Lhasa (2).JPG|thumb|View of metropolitan Chengguan District from the Potala Palace]]\n[[Chengguan District, Lhasa|Chengguan District]] is located on the middle reaches of the Lhasa River, with land that rises to the north and south of the river.\nIt is {{convert|28|km}} from east to west and {{convert|31|km}} from north to south.\nChengguan District is bordered by [[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]] to the west, [[Dagz\u00ea District]] to the east and [[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]] to the north. \n[[Gonggar County]] of Lhoka (Shannan) City lies to the south.{{sfn|Chengguan District of Lhasa, Baidu Baike}}\nChengguan District has an elevation of {{convert|3650|m}} and covers {{convert|525|km2}}.\nThe urban built-up area covers {{convert|60|km2}}. The average annual temperature is {{convert|8|\u00b0C}}.\nAnnual precipitation is about {{convert|500|mm}}, mostly falling between July and September.{{sfn|Chengguan District of Lhasa, Baidu Baike}}\n\nBefore the [[Incorporation of Tibet into the People's Republic of China|PRC takeover]] the city of Lhasa had a population of 25,000\u201330,000, or 45,000\u201350,000 if the large monasteries around the city are included.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=139}}\nThe old city formed a quadrangle about {{convert|3|km2}} around the [[Jokhang]] temple, about {{convert|1|km}} to the east of the [[Potala Palace]].{{sfn|Pommaret|2003|p=212}}\nDuring the period before the reforms introduced by [[Deng Xiaoping]] the old city of Lhasa was left largely intact, while bleakly functional compounds containing symmetrical dormitory-type buildings for both living and working were built apart from the city along the main roads.{{sfn|Pommaret|2003|p=213}}\n\nBy 1990 the city had expanded to cover {{convert|40|km2}}, with an official population of 160,000.{{sfn|Pommaret|2003|p=217}}\nThe 2000 official census gave a total population of 223,001, of which 171,719 lived in the areas administered by sub-districts and residential committees. \n133,603 had urban registrations and 86,395 had rural registrations, based on their place of origin.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\nBy 2013 the urban area  filled most of the natural Lhasa River valley in Chengguan District.{{sfn|Alexander|2013|p=368}}\nA 2011 book estimated that up to two-thirds of the city's residents are non-Tibetan, although the government states that Chengguan District as a whole is still 63% ethnic Tibetan.{{sfn|Johnson|2011|p=81}}\n\n===Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District===\n[[File:Tibet - Trek 2 - 03 Tsurpu Monastery (150294608).jpg|thumb|[[Tsurphu Monastery]] ]]\n[[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]] contains the western urban areas of Lhasa, developed in recent years with the new [[Lhasa railway station]], which begin about {{convert|12|km}} from the city center. \nIt covers an area of 2,704 square kilometers, with 94,969 acres of farmland.{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}\nThe district borders on the north Tibet grasslands in the northwest. The valley of the [[Duilong River]] leads south to the [[Lhasa River]]. The Duilong is {{convert|95|km}} in length.\nIn the south the district occupies part of the south bank of the Lhasa River.{{sfn|Ge Le|Li Tao|1996|p=35}}\nThe district has an average elevation of {{convert|4000|m}}, with a highest elevation of {{convert|5500|m}} and a lowest point at {{convert|3640|m}}.{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}\n\nThere are about 120 frost-free days annually.{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}\nAnnual mean temperature is {{convert|7|\u00b0C}}, with temperatures in January falling below {{convert|-10|\u00b0C}}\nAnnual precipitation is about {{convert|440|mm}}, with autumn rainfall of {{convert|310|mm}}. \nThe district is agriculturally rich and was used by the Tibetan kings as a source of food for Lhasa.{{sfn|Ge Le|Li Tao|1996|p=35}}\n\nThe seat of government is in the town of [[Donggar]].{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}\nThis is just {{convert|14|km}} from downtown Lhasa.{{sfn|Ge Le|Li Tao|1996|p=35}}\nIn 1992 there were 33,581 people in 6,500 households, with 94.28% of the people engaged in farming. \nAbout 90% of the people were ethnic Tibetan, with most people of other ethnicity living in Donggar.{{sfn|Ge Le|Li Tao|1996|p=35}}\nThe main mineral resources are coal, iron, clay, lead and zinc.{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Profile}}\n[[Tsurphu Monastery]], built in 1189, is treated as a regional cultural relic reserve.{{sfn|Lin|2014}}\nThe [[Nechung]] Monastery, former home of the [[Nechung Oracle]], is located in Naiquong township.{{sfn|Foster|Lee|Lin-Liu|Reiber|2012|p=787}}\nNechung was built by the [[5th Dalai Lama]] (1617\u201382).{{sfn|LaRocca|2006|p=28}}\n\n===Dagz\u00ea District===\n[[Dagz\u00ea District]] has a total area of {{convert|1373|km2}} and it contains the eastern urban areas of Lhasa. It has an average elevation of {{convert|4100|m}} above sea level, and descends from higher ground in the north and south to {{convert|3730|m}} in the lowest part of the Lhasa River valley.{{sfn|Dazi Overview, Dazi county}}\nThe average temperature is {{convert|7.5|\u00b0C}}, with about 130 days free of frost.\nAverage rainfall is {{convert|450|mm}}.{{sfn|Basic Dazi|, DIIB}}\nAbout 80%\u201390% of precipitation falls in the summer.{{sfn|Dazi, Baidu Baike}}\n\nAs of 2013 the total population was 29,152.{{sfn|Dazi Overview, Dazi county}}\nThe main occupation is agriculture. As of 2012 per capita income of farmers and herdsmen was 6,740 yuan.{{sfn|Dazi Overview, Dazi county}}\nIn 2010 there were 28 schools in the district, including one junior high school and one kindergarten, with 276 full-time teachers.\nThere is a district hospital and five township hospitals.\nThe Sichuan-Tibet Highway ([[China National Highway 318]]) runs through the district.{{sfn|Basic Dazi|, DIIB}}\nThe main monasteries in Dagz\u00ea are [[Ganden Monastery]] and [[Yerpa]].{{sfn|Dazi, Baidu Baike}}\n\n[[File:Dorje Ling Nunnery.jpg|thumb|Dorje Ling Nunnery in Damxung County, with adobe blocks curing in the foreground]]\n\n===Damxung County===\n[[File:Nyainqentanglha.JPG|thumb|Nyainqentanglha rising above Namtso]]\n[[Damxung County]] has an area of {{convert|10036|km2}}, with rugged topography.{{sfn|Damxung Land Resources}}\nAs of 2013 the population was 40,000, up from 35,000 in 1997.{{sfn|Damxung, Baidu Baike}}\nIt is tectonically active. On 6 October 2008 an earthquake measuring 6.6 on the [[Richter magnitude scale]] was reported.{{sfn|Mei|2008}}\nIn November 2010 a moderate quake in Damxung at 5.2 on the Richter scale shook office windows in Lhasa.\nThere were no casualties, but houses were damaged.{{sfn|Moderate quake jolts Tibet, Hindustan Times}}\n\nIn the extreme northeast of the county, [[Namtso]] lake has an area of {{convert|1920|km2}}, of which 45% lies in Damxung county. \nNamtso is one of the great lakes of the Tibetan plateau.\nThe [[Nyenchen Tanglha Mountains|Nyenchen Tanglha]] (or Nyainqentanglha) mountains extend along the northwest of the county.\n[[Mount Nyenchen Tanglha]] is the highest peak in the region, at {{convert|7111|m}}. \nThe Nyainq\u00eantanglha mountains define the watershed between northern and southern Tibet.{{sfn|Damxung, Baidu Baike}}\nA valley with elevation of about {{convert|4200|m}} runs parallel to the mountains to their southeast, sloping from northwest to southeast. \n30% of the county's total area is in the prairie of this valley.{{sfn|Mei|2008}}\n\nDamxung is cold and dry in the winter, cool and wet in summer, with very variable weather. The average annual temperature is {{convert|1.3|\u00b0C}}, with only 62 frost-free days. \nThe land is frozen from the start of November to the following March. Pasture has 90\u2013120 days for growth.\nAverage annual precipitation is {{convert|481|mm}}.{{sfn|Mei|2008}}\nNatural grasslands cover {{convert|693,171|ha}}, of which 68% is considered excellent.{{sfn|Damxung Land Resources}}\nAlmost all the people are engaged in rearing livestock, including [[yak]]s, [[sheep]], [[goat]]s and [[horse]]s.{{sfn|Mei|2008}}\n\nThe Qinghai-Tibet Highway ([[China National Highway 109]]) runs from east to west across the county.\n[[Damxung railway station]] links the county to the city of Lhasa to the south.{{sfn|Damxung, Baidu Baike}}\nThere is a large geothermal field at [[Yangbajain]] harnessed by generating units that deliver 25,181 kilowatts to the city of Lhasa to the south.{{sfn|Damxung Mineral Resources}}\nThe transmission line follows the [[Duilong River]] south through [[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]].{{sfn|Zhang|Tong|1982|p=320}}\nKangma Monastery is {{convert|16|km}} from the county seat. The meditation room has 1,213 carved stone reliefs of Buddha that are about three hundred years old.{{sfn|Lobsang|Zhang|2003}}\n[[Yangpachen Monastery]] in [[Yangbajain]] is historically the seat of the [[Shamarpa]]s of [[Karma Kagyu]].{{sfn|Dowman|1988|pp=129\u2013130}}\nThe monastery was destroyed during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but later was rebuilt.{{sfn|Yangpachen Monastery, Meiya Travel}}\n\n===Lh\u00fcnzhub County===\n[[File:Landscape of Tibet2.jpg|thumb|Countryside near [[Reting Monastery]] in the east of [[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]] ]]\n[[Lh\u00fcnzhub County]] is located around {{convert|65|km|abbr=on}} northeast of metropolitan Lhasa. \nIt includes the Pengbo River Valley and the upper reaches of the [[Lhasa River]].\nIt covers an area of {{convert|4512|km2|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}\nThe county is geologically complex, with an average elevation of {{convert|4000|m}}.{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}\nThe administrative center is the town of [[Lh\u00fcnzhub]].{{sfn|Linzhou, Baidu}}\n\nAs of 2000 the county had a total population of 50,895, of which 8,111 lived in a community designated as urban. 2,254 had non-agricultural registration and 48,362 had agricultural registration.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\nIn the south the Pengbo valley has an average elevation of {{convert|3680|m}} with a mild climate. The average temperature is {{convert|5.8|\u00b0C}}.{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}\nThe northern \"three rivers\" section, crossed by the Lhasa River and its tributary the [[Razheng River]], is mountainous and has an average elevation of {{convert|4200|m}}. \nIt has average annual temperature of {{convert|2.9|\u00b0C}} and is mostly pastoral, with yak, sheep and goats.{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}\n\nThe Pengbo valley is the main grain-producing region of Lhasa prefecture-level city and Tibet, with a total of {{convert|11931|ha}} of arable land.{{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}}\nCrops include barley, winter wheat, spring wheat, canola and vegetables such as potato.{{sfn|Linzhou Industry News, LSIIB}}\nLivestock includes yak, sheep, goats and horses.{{sfn|Linzhou County Profile, LSIIB}}\nIn 2010 the per capita income of farmers and herdsmen was 4,587 yuan.{{efn|A per capita income of 4,587 yuan converts to US$688 at an exchange rate of 0.15 dollars per yuan.{{sfn|XE Currency Table: CNY \u2013 Chinese Yuan Renminbi}} }}\nThe Pengbo valley has a long history of pottery-making. Products include braziers, flower pots, vases and jugs.{{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}}\nMining is an important source of income.\nIn 2011 the government has plans to more actively promote tourism.{{sfn|Government Work Report 2011}}\nThe [[Pangduo Hydro Power Station]] became operational in 2014.{{sfn|Guan|2013}}\nIt has been called the \"Tibetan Three Gorges\".{{sfn|Qin|2013}}\n\nThe county is a center of [[Tibetan Buddhism]]. \nThere were thirty-seven ''[[gompa]]s'' including twenty-five lamaseries with 919 monks and twelve nunneries with 844 nuns as of 2011.{{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}}\n[[Reting Monastery]] was built in 1056 by [[Dromt\u00f6n]] (1005\u20131064), a student of [[Ati\u015ba]].\nIt was the earliest monastery of the [[Gedain]] sect, and the patriarchal seat of that sect.{{sfn|Ling|2005|p=73}}\n\n===Maizhokunggar County===\n[[File:Drigung monastery3.jpg|thumb|View of the valley from [[Drigung Monastery]] ]]\n[[File:Drigung monastery4.jpg|thumb|Drigung Monastery]]\n[[Maizhokunggar County]] is located on the middle and upper sections of the [[Lhasa River]] and the west of [[Mila Mountain]].{{sfn|Sanpower Group donated RMB300,000 to Mozhugongka}}\nMila (or Mira) Mountain, at {{convert|5018|m}}, forms the watershed between the Lhasa River and the [[Nyang River]].{{sfn|Niyang River, Tibet Vista}}{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, Mozhugongka}}\nThe Gyama Zhungchu, which runs through Gyama Township, is a tributary of the Lhasa River.{{sfn|Brown|2013}}\nMaizhokunggar County is about {{convert|68|km}} east of [[Lhasa]], has an area of {{convert|5492|km2}} with an average elevation of more than {{convert|4000|m}}.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County Overview, Lhasa Municipal}}\nThe annual average temperature is {{convert|5.1|to|9.1|\u00b0C}}.\nThere are about 90 frost-free days each year. Annual rainfall is {{convert|515.9|mm}}.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, TibetOL}}\n[[China National Highway 318]] runs through the county from east to west.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County Overview, Lhasa Municipal}}\nThe 100&nbsp;MW [[Zhikong Hydro Power Station]] on the Lhasa River came into operation in September 2007.{{sfn|Zheng|2007}}\n\nThe total population as of 2010 was 48,561 people in 9,719 households, the great majority engaged in farming and herding.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County Overview, Lhasa Municipal}}\n98% of the population are ethnic Tibetan.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, China Intercontinental}}\nThe seat of government is in [[Kunggar]] in the west of the county.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, TibetOL}}\nMany of the people depend on farming or herding. Development efforts include increased farm animal husbandry, feedstock production, greenhouses for vegetables, and breeding programs.{{sfn|Mozhugongka county economic and social development}}\nCrops include barley, winter wheat, spring wheat, canola, peas, cabbage, carrots, eggplant, cucumbers, lettuce, spinach, green peppers, pumpkins, potatoes and other greenhouse crops.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, China Intercontinental}}\nThe economy is driven by mineral extraction, which was expected to account for 73.85% of total tax revenue in 2007 while employing 419 people.{{sfn|Mozhugongka county economic and social development}}\n\nTraditional folk handicrafts include pottery, willow basketwork, wooden objects, mats and gold and silver items.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, China Intercontinental}}\nThe county is especially noted for its pottery, which does not corrode, retains heat and has an ethnic style. It has a more-than-1000-year-old history.{{sfn|Ceramic skill, treasure of herdsmen}}\nThe [[Drikhung Thil Monastery]] of the [[Kagyu]] Sect was founded in 1179 by Lingchen Repa, a disciple of Phagmo Drupa.\nThe monastery is the home of the Drikhung Kagyu School of the Kagyu sect.{{sfn|Ling|2005|p=75}}\nThe ruined [[Gyama Palace]], in the Gyama Gully in the south of the county, was built by [[Namri Songtsen]] in the 6th century after he had gained control of the area from Supi.{{sfn|An|2003|p=66}}\n\n===Ny\u00eamo County===\n[[Ny\u00eamo County]] is located in the middle section of the Brahmaputra, {{convert|140|km}} from Lhasa.\nIt is mainly agricultural and pastoral, with an area of {{convert|3276|km2}} and an average elevation of {{convert|4000|m}}.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nThe [[Nimu Maqu River]] flows through the county from north to south.  \nThe [[Yarlung Tsangpo River]] forms its southern boundary.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County, Baidu Baike}}\nThe highest point is a peak at {{convert|7048.8|m}} above sea level, and the lowest point is where the Maqu River empties into the Brahmaputra at an elevation of {{convert|3701|m}}.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County, haotui}}\nThe county has a temperate semi-arid plateau monsoon climate, with about 100 frost-free days.\nAnnual rainfall is {{convert|324.2|mm}}.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\n\nNy\u00eamo County has its headquarters in [[Ny\u00eamo Town]].{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nThe county seat is {{convert|3809|m}} above sea level.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nAs of 2011 the total population was 30,844 people, of whom 28,474 were engaged in agriculture or herding.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nBy 2012 the per capita income of farmers and herdsmen had reached 6,881 yuan.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County 2012 Summary...}}\nIn the 7th century Ny\u00eamo was producing printing materials, clay-based incense and wooden-sole shoes.{{sfn|Shakabpa|2009|p=78}}\nNy\u00eamo's long tradition of making paper and printing texts using woodblocks dates back to this period. \nNy\u00eamo County has China's first museum of Tibetan text.{{sfn|Inside Nimu, China Tibet Online}}\nThere are 22 temples. As of 2011 there were 118 monks and 99 nuns.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nThe [[Ny\u00eamo Chekar monastery]] is known for its 16th century murals depicting reincarnations of the [[Samding Dorje Phagmo]].{{sfn|Diemberger|2014|p=27}}\n\n===Q\u00fcx\u00fc County===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 135-S-15-07-22, Tibetexpedition, Ufer, Wartende.jpg|thumb|[[Yarlung Tsangpo]] ferry near Q\u00fcx\u00fc 1939]]\n[[Q\u00fcx\u00fc County]] has a total area of {{convert|1680|km2}}, with an average elevation of {{convert|3650|m}}.{{sfn|Booming Lhasa Qushui, CCTV}}\nThe county is in the Yarlung Tsangpo valley, and is mostly relatively flat, but rises to the [[Nyainq\u00eantanglha Mountains]] in the north.\nThe Lhasa River runs south through the eastern part of the county to its confluence with the Yarlung Tsangpo River, which forms the southern boundary of the county.\nThe lowest elevation is {{convert|3500|m}}, and the highest summit elevation is {{convert|5894|m}}.{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, CGN}}\nQ\u00fcx\u00fc County has about 150 days a year without frost.\nAnnual precipitation is {{convert|441.9|mm|in|sp=us}}.{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, CGN}}\n\nQ\u00fcx\u00fc County has its headquarters in [[Q\u00fcx\u00fc|Q\u00fcx\u00fc Town]].{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, CGN}}\nThe fifth census in 2000 recorded a population of 29,690.{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, CGN}}\nThe county seat has been growing fast, and had 5,000 people by 2002.{{sfn|Booming Lhasa Qushui, CCTV}}\nChina National Highway 318 runs through Q\u00fcx\u00fc County from Lhasa towards the west. Bridges span the Lhasa River and the Yarlung Tsangpo River.{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, Lhasa Tourism}}\n\nQ\u00fcx\u00fc County is semi-agricultural and crops grown are mainly [[highland barley]], winter wheat, spring wheat, peas and rapeseed. \nApples and walnuts are also produced.\nAnimal husbandry is also strong, with the main animals farmed including yak, cattle, goats, sheep, horses, donkeys, pigs, and chickens.{{sfn|Lhasa Qushui Introduction, Lhasa Tourism}}\nAs of 2002 the per capita net income of farmers and herdsmen was 1,960 yuan.{{sfn|Booming Lhasa Qushui, CCTV}}\nThe [[Nyethang Drolma Lhakhang Temple]] is located in Q\u00fcx\u00fc County, said to have been founded in 1055 by [[Dromt\u00f6n]], a pupil of [[Ati\u015ba]].{{sfn|Qushui & Duilongdeqing County}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\nThe demographics of Lhasa prefecture-level city are difficult to define precisely due to the way in which administrative boundaries have been drawn, and the way in which statistics are collected.\nThe population of Lhasa prefectural-level city is about 500,000, of whom about 80% are ethnic Tibetan and most of the others are ethnic Han Chinese. Approximately 250,000 people live in the city and in towns, most of them in or near Chengguan District, and the remainder live in rural areas.\n\n===Ethnicity===\n[[File:Tibetan woman.JPG|thumb|Tibetan woman with prayer wheel in Lhasa street]]\nThe 2000 census give the following breakdown for the population of the prefecture-level city as a whole:{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|p=25}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! !!Total Population !! &nbsp;Han Population !! &nbsp;Tibetan Population\n|-\n|Subdistricts (''jiedao'') ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 171,719 ||style=\"text-align:right\"|62,226 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 104,203\n|-\n|Towns (''zhen'') ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 60,117 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 3,083 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 56,614\n|-\n|Townships (''xiang'') ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 242,663 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 15,275 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 226,307\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|'''Total''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''474,499''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''80,584''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''387,124'''\n|}\nThe 2000 census counts more than 105,000 people in Chengguan District who are registered elsewhere. \nMost of them are Han, with agricultural registrations.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\nOutside Chengguan District, in 2000 the rural townships almost all had Han populations below 2.85%, other than one in Duilongdeqing County and one in Qushui County, both near the metropolitan district of Lhasa. Urban towns other than [[Yangbajain]] had Han populations of between 2.86% and 11.25%. Within the metropolitan district Han population ranged from 11.26% to 11.25% in the southern rural township to 46.56% to 47.46% in the city street offices.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|p=26}}\nHan migrants accounted for 20% of the population, but held a much higher percentage of the higher-status office and service-sector jobs. \nHans also dominated construction, mining and trade.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|p=26\u201327}}\n\n[[File:Butter Market, Lhasa.jpg|thumb|Butter Market, Lhasa]]\n[[File:Nomad camp above Tsurphu Gompa 2.JPG|thumb|Nomad camp above Tsurphu Gompa in 1993]]\nAccording to the November 2000 census, the ethnic distribution in Lhasa Prefecture-level City was as follows:{{sfn|Tabulation on Nationalities of 2000...}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"8\"| Major ethnic groups in Lhasa Prefecture-level City by district or county, 2000 census\n|-\n!\n!Total!!colspan = 2 | [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]]!!colspan = 2 | [[Han Chinese]]!!colspan = 2 | others\n|-\n|Chengguan District||style=\"text-align:right\"|223,001||style=\"text-align:right\"|140,387||style=\"text-align:right\"|63.0%||style=\"text-align:right\"|76,581||style=\"text-align:right\"|34.3%||style=\"text-align:right\"|6,033||style=\"text-align:right\"|2.7%\n|-\n|Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District||style=\"text-align:right\"|40,543||style=\"text-align:right\"|38,455||style=\"text-align:right\"|94.8%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|1,868||style=\"text-align:right\"|4.6%||style=\"text-align:right\"|220||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.5%\n|-\n|Dagz\u00ea District||style=\"text-align:right\"|24,906||style=\"text-align:right\"|24,662||style=\"text-align:right\"|99.0%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|212||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.9%||style=\"text-align:right\"|32||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.1%\n|-\n|Damxung County||style=\"text-align:right\"|39,169||style=\"text-align:right\"|38,689||style=\"text-align:right\"|98.8%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|347||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.9%||style=\"text-align:right\"|133||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.3%\n|-\n|Lh\u00fcnzhub County||style=\"text-align:right\"|50,895||style=\"text-align:right\"|50,335||style=\"text-align:right\"|98.9%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|419||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.8%||style=\"text-align:right\"|141||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.3%\n|-\n|Maizhokunggar County||style=\"text-align:right\"|38,920||style=\"text-align:right\"|38,567||style=\"text-align:right\"|99.1%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|220||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.6%||style=\"text-align:right\"|133||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.3%\n|-\n|Ny\u00eamo County||style=\"text-align:right\"|27,375||style=\"text-align:right\"|27,138||style=\"text-align:right\"|99.1%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|191||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.7%||style=\"text-align:right\"|46||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.2%\n|-\n|Q\u00fcx\u00fc County||style=\"text-align:right\"|29,690||style=\"text-align:right\"|28,891||style=\"text-align:right\"|97.3%\n|style=\"text-align:right\"|746||style=\"text-align:right\"|2.5%||style=\"text-align:right\"|53||style=\"text-align:right\"|0.2%\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|Total!!style=\"text-align:right\"|474,499!!style=\"text-align:right\"|387,124!!style=\"text-align:right\"|81.6%\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|80,584!!style=\"text-align:right\"|17.0%!!style=\"text-align:right\"|6,791!!style=\"text-align:right\"|1.4%\n|}\n\n===Administrative divisions===\n[[File:Young monk in meditation cell, Yerpa, Tibet. 1993.jpg|thumb|Young monk in meditation cell, [[Yerpa]], Dagz\u00ea County, 1993]]\nLhasa metropolitan district includes most of the built-up area, which counts as urban, and four rural townships. \nThe counties also contain urban towns, of which there are nine in the prefectural municipality.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\n\nOfficial census figures for 2000 are:{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! !!Total<br/>Population !!&nbsp;City/Town<br/>Population !!&nbsp;Non-Agricultural<br/>Registration !!&nbsp;Agricultural<br/>Registration \n|-\n| Chengguan District ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 223,001 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 171,719 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 133,603 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 86,395\n|-\n| Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 40,543 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 17,197 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 3,836 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 36,608\n|-\n| Dagz\u00ea District ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 24,906 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 7,382 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 1,464 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 23,431\n|-\n| Damxung County ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 39,169 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 8,530 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 2,023 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 36,975\n|-\n| Lh\u00fcnzhub County ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 50,895 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 8,111 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 2,254 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 48,362\n|-\n| Maizhokunggar County ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 38,920 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 5,409 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 1,526 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 37,384\t\n|-\n| Ny\u00eamo County ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 27,375 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 6,082 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 1,190 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 25,981\n|-\n| Q\u00fcx\u00fc County ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 29,690 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 7,406 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 1,564 ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 28,057\t\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:right\"| '''Municipality total''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''474,499''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''231,836''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''147,460''' ||style=\"text-align:right\"| '''323,193'''\n|}\nThe census figures differ considerably from the Tibet Statistical Yearbooks for the same period, since the yearbook only includes the registered population and counts them based on place of origin rather than place of residence. The 1990 census used an approach similar to the yearbook, so the numbers are misleading, but the 2000 census tried to count people who had actually been present in Lhasa for over six months. The census distinguishes between \"agricultural\" and \"non-agricultural\" registration, but this does not reflect the actual occupations of the people. Many with an \"agricultural\" registration may in fact work in the city or in a town.\nAlso, the census was taken in November, when many of the ethnic Han workers in seasonal industries such as construction would have been away from Tibet. \nFinally, the census does not count the military.{{sfn|Yeh|Henderson|2008|pp=21\u201325}}\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Highways===\n[[File:Mi La mountain pass Tibet.jpg|thumb|[[China National Highway 318]] at [[Mila Mountain]] pass]]\n[[China National Highway 318]] enters the prefecture-level city from the east at [[Mila Mountain]], where it reaches an elevation of {{convert|5000|m|sigfig=5}}.{{sfn|A journey in Tibet: Mila Mountain}}\nThe highway runs through [[Maizhokunggar County]] from east to west.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County Overview, Lhasa Municipal}}\nIt continues along the south bank of the Lhasa River through Dagz\u00ea County, then crosses to the north of the river in Chengguan District and runs through the center of the urban district. It turns south to cross [[Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District]], where it is joined by 109, and continues down the west side of the Lhasa River through Q\u00fcx\u00fc County, and then along the north shore of the Yarlung Tsangpo through Ny\u00eamo County, and onward to the west.{{sfn|Lhasa region map, China Mike}}\n\n[[File:Galashan Tunnel, Tibet - Flickr - archer10 (Dennis).jpg|thumb|Galashan Tunnel of [[Lhasa Airport Expressway]] ]]\n[[China National Highway 109]] (the Qinghai\u2013Tibet Highway) runs through Damxung County from the northeast to southwest, then turns to the southeast at [[Yangbajain]].{{sfn|Lhasa region map, China Mike}}\nIt then runs through Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District along the [[Duilong River]] valley, to join [[China National Highway 318]] just west of Lhasa.{{sfn|Duilongdeqing County, Administrative divisions}}\nThe [[Lhasa Airport Expressway]] from Lhasa to [[Lhasa Gonggar Airport]] in [[Lhoka (Shannan) Prefecture]] is the first expressway in the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]].{{sfn|430 million yuan in place for Lhasa-Gongkar ... 2010}}\nConstruction began in April, 2009. The expressway is {{convert|37.8|km}} long and has four lanes.{{sfn|Shi|2011}}\n\n===Railway===\n[[File:Qingzang railway Train 01.jpg|thumb|Railway in Damxung about {{convert|20|km}} north of [[Yangbajain]] ]]\nThe [[Qinghai\u2013Tibet Railway]] runs through the Lhasa prefecture-level city beside the Qinghai\u2013Tibet Highway through Damxung County and Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District.{{sfn|Duilongdeqing County, Administrative divisions}}\nIt terminates at [[Lhasa railway station]] in [[Niu New Area]] (Liuwu Township).{{sfn|Lhasa Railway Station, Tripadvisor}}\nThe terminus of the Qinghai\u2013Tibet line, this station is over {{convert|3600|m}} above sea level, and is its largest passenger transport station.\nIt includes a clinic with oxygen treatment facilities. The station uses solar energy for heating.{{sfn|Lhasa Railway Station Duilongdeqing County}}\nThe [[Liuwu Bridge]] links central Lhasa to Lhasa railway station and the newly developed Niu New Area of Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District on the south bank of the Lhasa River.\nResidents in the area were resettled to make way for the new development.{{sfn|Resettlement and railroad construction in Lhasa}}\n\n===Power===\n[[File:Yangbajing.jpg|thumb|[[Yangbajain Geothermal Field]] ]]\nThe Yangbajain Geothermal Station was established in 1977 to exploit the [[Yangbajain Geothermal Field]] in Damxung.{{sfn|Yangbajing, Ministry of Culture}}\nIt is the first geothermal power station to be built in Tibet and is the largest geothermal steam power plant in China.{{sfn|An|2003|p=27}}\n4,000&nbsp;kW of electricity from Yangbajain began to be delivered to Lhasa in 1981 along a transmission line that followed the Doilung Qu River.{{sfn|Zhang|Tong|1982|p=320}}\nIt was the main power supply for Lhasa until the [[Yamdrok Hydropower Station]] came into operation.{{sfn|An|2003|p=27}}\nBy the end of 2000 eight steam turbo generators had been installed at the Yangbajain Geothermal Station, each with capacity of 3,000&nbsp;kW, giving a total of 25,000&nbsp;kW.{{sfn|An|2003|p=27}}\nThe geothermal field delivers 25,181 kilowatts, or 100 million kilowatts annually, to the city of Lhasa to the south.{{sfn|Damxung Mineral Resources}}\n\nThe [[Pangduo Hydro Power Station]] has been called \"Tibet's Three Gorges Dam\".\nIt impounds the Lhasa River in Pondo Township of Lh\u00fcnzhub County, about {{convert|63|km}} from Lhasa.{{sfn|'Tibet's Three Gorges Dam' starts operation}}\nIt is at an elevation of {{convert|13390|ft}} above sea level, upstream from the 100MW [[Zhikong Dam]] at {{convert|12660|ft}}.{{sfn|Buckley|2014|p=52}}\nThe [[rock-fill dam]] impounds {{convert|1,170,000,000|m3}} of water.{{sfn|Tibet's biggest water-related project launched}}\nThe power station has total installed capacity of 160 MW.{{sfn|Guan|2013}}\n\nThe [[Zhikong Hydro Power Station]] lies between the middle and lower reaches of the Lhasa River, also called the Kyi River.{{sfn|Zheng|2007}}\nIt is about {{convert|100|km}} northeast of [[Lhasa]], in Maizhokunggar County.{{sfn|Pletcher|2010|p=299}}{{sfn|Hydroelectric Power Plants in China, Platts}}\nIt is at an elevation of {{convert|12660|ft}} above sea level, downstream from the Pangduo Hydro Power Station.{{sfn|Buckley|2014|p=52}}\nThe Zhikong Dam, a [[rock-fill dam]], is {{convert|50|m}} tall.{{sfn|China region completes work on 100-MW Zhikong}}\nIt impounds {{convert|225000000|m3}} of water.{{sfn|Zheng|2007}}\nInstalled capacity is 100&nbsp;MW.{{sfn|Hydroelectric Power Plants in China, Platts}}\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[File:20060731122736 - \u5f53\u96c4\u7ad9.jpg|thumb|[[Damxung railway station]] ]]\nThe rural counties generally have numerous primary schools at the village level, with high levels of attendance, and at least one secondary school. \nIn 2010 there were 28 schools in Dagz\u00ea County, including one junior high school and one kindergarten.{{sfn|Basic Dazi|, DIIB}}\nAs of 2009 there were 37 primary and secondary school buildings in Damxung County.{{sfn|Damxung, Baidu Baike}}\nMaizhokunggar County has one high school, 14 full primary schools and 74 village schools.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, China Intercontinental}}\nNy\u00eamo County has 24 primary and secondary schools, including one junior high school.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nAs of 2002 Q\u00fcx\u00fc County had one County Middle School, and 18 primary schools.{{sfn|Booming Lhasa Qushui, CCTV}}\nOutside Lhasa most of the Tibetans do not understand the Chinese language, so Tibetan is the natural language for basic instruction. However, this may be affected by the availability of teachers and the preference of the local administration.{{sfn|Cheng|2011|p=296}}\nAs of 2003 the former bilingual mode of instruction had been changed to giving instruction in Chinese in some of the counties near Lhasa. \nExamination results were already poor in subjects such as mathematics and physics. Marks dropped further after the change.{{sfn|Cheng|2011|p=297}}\n\nSome of the township seats have a small clinic. Most have only a health station, usually poorly supplied.{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=43}}\nThere is a county hospital and five township hospitals in Dagz\u00ea County.{{sfn|Basic Dazi|, DIIB}}\nThere were seven hospitals in Damxung in 2009, including a county hospital, with a total of 40 beds.{{sfn|Damxung Tibet Introduction, CCTV}}\nThe first drug rehabilitation center in Tibet was being constructed in Duilongdeqing County in 2009. It was planned to provide physiological rehabilitation, psychological therapy and job training for up to 150 drug addicts.{{sfn|First drug rehabilitation center in Tibet ... 2009}}\nLh\u00fcnzhub County has 23 health care establishments, including a County People's Hospital with 30 beds.{{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}}\nMaizhokunggar has been selected as a Cooperative Medical System experimental site, which has resulted in a very high percentage of people with health care coverage.{{sfn|Zhongwei |2006|p=474}}\nNy\u00eamo County has a county hospital with 42 medical staff, eight rural health centers and 26 village clinics.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\n\nThe local television stations are Xizang TV (XZTV) and Lhasa Broadcasting and Television Center.{{sfn|Buckley|2012|p=141}}\nLh\u00fcnzhub County has a local radio and television station. TV coverage is received by 72.1% of the population, and radio by 83.4% of the population.{{sfn|Linzhou, TibetOL}}\nIn Maizhokunggar County television is available to 36% of the population and radio to 48%.{{sfn|Mozhugongka County, China Intercontinental}}\nThere is a county television station in Ny\u00eamo County.{{sfn|Ny\u00eamo County Overview, Lhasa Municipality}}\nAs of 2002 in Q\u00fcx\u00fc County 98% of the population received radio coverage and 94% received television.{{sfn|Booming Lhasa Qushui, CCTV}}\nIn 2015 there were 359,000 fixed line telephone subscribers in the whole of Tibet.\nThe rugged high-altitude terrain makes it expensive to provide telecommunications services.\nThe first mobile phone service was launched in 1993 with just one base station in Lhasa, and as late as 2005 mobile phones were expensive status symbols. Since then both mobile phones and internet usage have grown fast.{{sfn|Salvacion|2015}}\n\nAs of 1996 the sole prison (''jianyu'') for judicially-sentenced political prisoners in Tibet was TAR Prison No. 1, also called Drapchi Prison after the neighborhood in Lhasa where it stands. It is for men serving sentences of five or more years. There is a labor camp (''laogai'') in Lhasa for men serving shorter sentences.{{sfn|Barnett|1996|p=82}}\nThere are various other institutions where prisoners from ''Lhasa shi'' are held while they are being investigated, or where they undergo reform-through-labor.{{sfn|Barnett|1996|p=86}}\n\n==Temples and monasteries==\n[[File:Monks at Ganden monastery, 2013.jpg|thumb|Monks at [[Ganden Monastery]] in Dagz\u00ea County]]\nBuddhism was adopted as the official religion of Tibet by king [[Songts\u00e4n Gampo]] (died 649) at a time when the rise of Hinduism was sweeping away [[Buddhism]] in India, the land of its birth. Over the next two centuries Buddhism became established in Tibet, now the center of the religion.{{sfn|Landon|1905|p=29}}\n[[Tibetan Buddhism]] would become a pervasive influence on the lives of the people.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=139}}\nThe first monastery, ''Samy\u00e9'', was founded by [[Trisong Detsen]] ({{circa|740\u2013798}}).\nIts buildings were arranged in a mandala pattern after the Odantapuri monastery in [[Bihar]]. The three-story monastery was completed in 766 and consecrated in 767. \nSeven Tibetans took monastic vows in a ceremony that marked the start of the long Tibetan tradition of monastic Buddhism.{{sfn|Powers|2007|p=148}}{{efn|Multi-storey buildings such as monasteries in the earthquake-prone Lhasa region usually have battered walls, massive at the base and lighter higher up, with flexible timber frames. Preferably adobe brick is used for the upper floors. The roofs are flat, waterproofed with pounded limestone, and provide living space.{{sfn|Alexander|2013|p=34}} }}\n\n===Early foundations===\n[[Yerpa]], on a hillside in Dagze County, is known for its meditation cave connected with Songts\u00e4n Gampo.{{sfn|Historic Dra Yerpa Temple in Tibet, Xinhua}}\nThe cliffs contain some of the earliest known meditation sites in Tibet, some dating back to pre-Buddhist times. There are a number of small temples, shrines and hermitages. \nSongts\u00e4n Gampo's queen, Monza Triucham, founded the Dra Yerpa temple here.{{sfn|Dorje|1999|pp=68\u201369}}\n[[Jokhang]] in Chengguan District is the most sacred temple in Tibet, built in the 7th century when Songts\u00e4n Gampo transferred his capital to Lhasa.\nIt was designed to house an image of Buddha that the Nepalese queen Tritsun had brought. Later rulers and [[Dalai Lama]]s enlarged and elaborated the temple.{{sfn|Buckley|2012|p=142}}\n\n[[Ramoche Temple]] to the north of Jokhang is considered the most important temple in Lhasa after [[Jokhang]], and was completed about the same time.{{sfn|Dowman|1988|p=59}}\n[[Muru Nyingba Monastery]] is a small monastery located between the larger Jokhang temple and [[Barkhor]] in the city of Lhasa. \nIt was the Lhasa seat of the former State Oracle who had his main residence at [[Nechung]] Monastery.{{sfn|Dowman|1988|p=40}}\nIt was destroyed during the persecution of Buddhism under [[Langdarma]] ({{circa|838\u2013841}}) but rebuilt by [[Ati\u015ba]] (980\u20131054).\nThe monastery was part of the [[Sakya]] sect at one time. but became [[Gelug]] under [[3rd Dalai Lama|Sonam Gyatso]], the 3rd Dalai Lama (1543\u201389).{{sfn|Dorje|1999|p=88}}\n\n===Middle period===\n[[File:Dorje Phagmo incarnation in 16th century mural at Myemo Chekar.png|thumb|Mural in [[Ny\u00eamo Chekar monastery]] of an incarnation of [[Samding Dorje Phagmo]] ]]\nThe [[Nyethang Drolma Temple]] is southwest of Lhasa, {{convert|36|km}} from the county seat and {{convert|33|km}} from Lhasa.{{sfn|Nie Tong Temple, CTO}} \nIt is in [[Ny\u00eatang|Ny\u00e9tang]], Q\u00fcx\u00fc County.{{sfn|Chinese Buddhist temple tour}}\nSome sources say that [[Ati\u015ba]] (980\u20131054) built the monastery, which was expanded after his death by his pupil [[Dromt\u00f6n]] (1004\u201364).{{sfn|Chinese Buddhist temple tour}} \nAnother version says that Dromt\u00f6n raised funds to build the temple to commemorate his old friend.{{sfn|Nie Tong Temple, CTO}}\nDromt\u00f6n built [[Reting Monastery]] in  Lh\u00fcnzhub County in 1056.\nIt was the earliest monastery of the [[Gedain]] sect, and the patriarchal seat of that sect.{{sfn|Ling|2005|p=73}}\nIn 1240 a Mongol force sacked Reting monastery and killed 500 people. The ''[[gompa]]'' was rebuilt.{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=126}}\nWhen the Gedain sect joined the Gelug sect in the 16th century the monastery adopted the reincarnation system.{{sfn|Ling|2005|p=73}}\n\n[[Tsurphu Monastery]] in Doilungd\u00eaq\u00ean District was built in 1189 and is treated as a regional cultural relic reserve.{{sfn|Lin|2014}}\nThe monastery was founded by [[D\u00fcsum Khyenpa, 1st Karmapa Lama]], founder of [[Karma Kagyu]] school.\nIt is the main Kagyu temple.{{sfn|Lhasa Duilongdeqing County Introduction}}\nThe [[Drigung Monastery]] of the [[Kagyu]] Sect was founded in 1179 in Maizhokunggar County.\nIt is the home of the Drikhung Kagyu School of the Kagyu sect.{{sfn|Ling|2005|p=75}}\nAt one time Drigung was highly influential in both the political and religious spheres. \nIt was destroyed in 1290 by Mongols led by a general from the rival [[Sakya]] sect, and although rebuilt was never able to regain its power.{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=129}}\n\n[[Yangpachen Monastery]] in [[Yangbajain]], Damxung County was historically the seat of the [[Shamarpa]]s of [[Karma Kagyu]].{{sfn|Dowman|1988|pp=129\u2013130}}\nIt is the main monastery of the Red Hat school of the Karma Kagyu sect. It was built in 1490, and through extensive repairs and additions grew into a major architectural complex that contained a large collection of cultural relics. The Red Hat school of Karma Kagyu died out in 1791.{{sfn|Yangpachen Monastery, Meiya Travel}}\nOther monasteries founded outside the Gelug tradition include [[Taklung Monastery]] of the [[Kagyu]] school, founded in 1180 in Lh\u00fcnzhub County,{{sfn|Dorje|Kapstein|1991|p=478}} and [[Ny\u00eamo Chekar monastery]] of the [[Bodongpa]] school, founded in the 16th century in Ny\u00eamo County.{{sfn|Diemberger|2014|p=239}}\n\n===Gelug foundations===\n[[File:Ganden monastery, 2013.jpg|thumb|[[Ganden Monastery]] in Dagze County, the first [[Gelug]] foundation]]\n\n[[Ganden Monastery]] was built after 1409 at the initiative of [[Je Tsongkhapa]], founder of the [[Gelug]] sect, and is the most important of this sect. It is {{convert|57|km}} from Lhasa on the slopes of Wangbori Mountain at an elevation of {{convert|3800|m}}, on the south bank of the Lhasa River in Dagze County. The mountain is said to have the shape of a reclining elephant.\nThe monastery includes Buddha halls, palace residences, Buddhist colleges and other buildings.{{sfn|Gandain Monastery, China Intercontinental|p=2}}\n\n[[Drepung Monastery]] in Chengguan District was founded in 1416 by Jamyang Choge Tashi Palden (1397\u20131449), one of [[Tsongkhapa]]'s main disciples.\nIt was named after the sacred abode in South India of Shridhanyakataka.{{sfn|Dorje|1999|p=113}}\nAt one time Drepung Monastery, with up to 10,000 resident monks, was the largest in the world. [[Sera Monastery]] was not much smaller.{{sfn|Bisht|2008|p=25}}\nSera Monastery, about {{convert|2|mi}} north of Lhasa, was founded in 1419 by Jamchen Ch\u00f6j\u00e9 Shakya Yesh\u00e9 (1354\u20131435), a close disciple of Tsongkhapa.{{sfn|Cabez\u00f3n|2008}}\nGanden, Drepung and Sera are called the great \"Three Seats of Learning\" of the Gulugpa school.{{sfn|Hackett|Bernard|2013|p=325}}\n\nThe [[Nechung]] Monastery, former home of the [[Nechung Oracle]], is located in Naiquong township, also in [[Duilongdeqing County]].{{sfn|Foster|Lee|Lin-Liu|Reiber|2012|p=787}} Nechung was built by the [[5th Dalai Lama]] (1617\u201382).{{sfn|LaRocca|2006|p=28}} Other Gelug foundations include [[Sanga Monastery]] (1419, Dagz\u00ea County), [[Ani Tsankhung Nunnery]] (15th century, Chengguan District), [[Kundeling Monastery]] (1663, Chengguan District), and [[Tsomon Ling]] (17th century, Chengguan District).\n\n===Revolution and reconstruction===\n[[File:Monastery ruins, Yerpa 1993.JPG|thumb|[[Yerpa]] ruins in 1993]]\n[[File:Jokhang Temple in Tibet.jpg|thumb|[[Jokhang]], now a World Heritage Site]]\nMost of the monasteries in the prefecture-level city suffered damage, and many were destroyed, before and during the [[Cultural Revolution]] (1966\u201376).\nJokhang was used as a military barracks and a slaughterhouse during the Cultural Revolution, and then as a hotel for Chinese officials.{{sfn|Buckley|2012|p=142}}\nMany of the statues were taken, or were damaged or destroyed, so most of the present statues are recent copies.\nJokhang was designated a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] in 2000.{{sfn|Buckley|2012|p=143}}\nRamoche Temple was badly damaged during the Cultural Revolution but has been restored with assistance from the Swiss.{{sfn|Kelly|Bellezza|2008|p=113}}\nThe Nyethang Drolma Temple survived the [[Cultural Revolution]] without much damage, and was able to preserve most of its valuable artifacts, due to the intervention of Premier [[Zhou Enlai]] at the request of the government of what is now [[Bangladesh]].{{sfn|Fenton|1999|p=93}}\n\nReting Monastery was devastated by the [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]] during the Cultural Revolution, and has only been partially restored.{{sfn|Mayhew|Kohn|2005|p=142}}\nTsurphu monastery was reduced to rubble, but the huge temples and chanting halls have been rebuilt.{{sfn|McCue|2010|p=134}}\nBefore and during the [[Cultural Revolution]] (1966\u201376) [[Drigung Monastery]] was looted of almost all its collection of statues, [[stupa]]s, [[thangka]]s, manuscripts and other objects apart from a few small statues that the monks managed to hide. The buildings were severely damaged.\nReconstruction began in 1983 and seven of the fifteen temples were rebuilt.{{sfn|Drikung Thil, Drikung Kagyu Order}}\nYangpachen Monastery was destroyed during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but later was rebuilt.{{sfn|Yangpachen Monastery, Meiya Travel}}\n\nGanden Monastery was completely destroyed during the rebellion of 1959. \nIn 1966 it was severely shelled by [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guard]] artillery, and monks had to dismantle the remains.{{sfn|Dowman|1988|p=99}} \nThe buildings were reduced to rubble using dynamite during the Cultural Revolution.{{sfn|Buckley|2012|p=174}}\nRe-building has continued since the 1980s.{{sfn|Dowman|1988|p=99\u2013100}}\nNechung was almost completely destroyed but has been largely restored.\nThere is a huge new statue of Guru Rinpoche ([[Padmasambhava]]) on the second floor.{{sfn|Mayhew|Kohn|2005|p=22}}\n\nNine sites in the Lhasa valley were listed in 1985 by the TAR Cultural Relics Authority as \"regionally protected buildings\". \nThese were Tsangkung Nunnery, Meru Monastery and Great Kashmiri Mosque in the old city, and the Karmashar Temple, Meru Nyingba Monastery and Northern, Southern, Eastern and Western Rigsum Temples elsewhere in the former prefecture.{{sfn|Alexander|2013|p=374}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist |colwidth = 30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |ref = {{harvid|430 million yuan in place for Lhasa-Gongkar ... 2010}} |url = http://chinatibet.people.com.cn/7090166.html |work=China Tibet Online\n |title=430 million yuan in place for Lhasa-Gongkar airport expressway |date=2010-08-02 |accessdate=2015-02-16 }}\n* {{cite web\n |ref={{harvid|A journey in Tibet: Mila Mountain}} \n |url = http://en.people.cn/90782/7747404.html \n |title = A journey in Tibet: Mila Mountain \n |date=2012-03-05 \n |work=People's Daily Online \n |accessdate=2015-02-20 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220193317/http://en.people.cn/90782/7747404.html \n |archivedate=2015-02-20 \n}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Alexander|first=Andr\u00e9|title=The Traditional Lhasa House: Typology of an Endangered Species\n |url = https://books