801/t20080116_338883.htm |last=Zheng |first=Peng |title=Lhasa River Zhi Kong hydroelectric power station put into operation |date=2007-09-24 |work=China Tibet Information Center |accessdate=2015-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206175256/http://en.tibet.cn/news/today/200801/t20080116_338883.htm |archivedate=2015-02-06 }}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|title=Income Inequality, Unequal Health Care Access, and Mortality in China|last=Zhongwei |first=Zhao|journal=Population and Development Review|volume=32|issue=3 |date=September 2006|publisher=Population Council|jstor=20058900|doi=10.1111/j.1728-4457.2006.00133.x|pages=461\u2013483}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Lhasa (prefecture-level city)}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Township-level divisions of Lhasa}}\n{{Tibet Autonomous Region}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Provincial capitals of China}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lhasa| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Tibet]]\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Tibet]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lhasa_(prefecture-level_city)"}
{"title_page": "Satham Podathey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Satham Podathey\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vasanth]]\n| producer       = C. Shanker<br />R. S. Senthil Kumar\n| writer         = [[Vasanth]]\n| starring       = [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]]<br />[[Padmapriya Janakiraman|Padmapriya]]<br />[[Nithin Sathya]]<br />[[Raaghav]]<br />[[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]]<br />[[Suhasini Mani Ratnam|Suhasini]]\n| music          = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cinematography = Dinesshkumaar\n| editing        = Sathisshkurosowaa\n| studio         = Kaivallya Entertainment\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2007|09|14}}\n| runtime        = 157 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Satham Podathey''''' ({{lang-en|Don't make a sound}}) is a 2007 Tamil [[psychological thriller film]] written and directed by [[Vasanth]] and produced by Shankar and Senthilnathan. It stars [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]], [[Padmapriya Janakiraman|Padmapriya]] and [[Nithin Sathya]] in the lead roles whilst [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]], [[Suhasini Mani Ratnam|Suhasini]], [[Premji Amaren|Premji]] and [[Raaghav]] play cameo roles. The film, which is based on a true incident, has music scored by [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], which received rave reviews. The film was released on 14 September 2007 to positive reviews. The film was simultaneously dubbed in [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] as ''Kelkaatha Shabdam''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story revolves around Bhanumathy ([[Padmapriya]]) who marries Rathnavel Kalidas ([[Nithin Sathya]]), a man who works in railways as a [[hockey]] player. He married Bhanu by hiding the facts that he is [[impotent]] and a recovering [[alcoholism|alcoholic]]. Soon, the relationship turns sour when the couple realizes that Rathnavel is impotent after a [[gynecology|gynecologist]] ([[Suhasini]]) tells them so. In spite of family pressures to get a mutual [[divorce]], the old-fashioned Bhanu decides to go ahead with the marriage by adopting a child. With the baby's arrival, Rathnavel unfortunately becomes more insecure and tells Bhanu that the child reminds him about his weakness. Unfortunately, all hell breaks loose when Bhanu realizes that her husband was an alcoholic who knew about his impotency and had betrayed her. Rathnavel, in his anger, beats up Bhanu until she is almost unconscious. A few days later, she files for a [[divorce]] and stays with her parents for some days. Bhanu later meets Ravichandran ([[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]]), a happy-go-lucky guy who is a friend of her brother ([[Raaghav]]). Ravi proposes to Bhanu, and they later get married, but Rathnavel, who had vowed to make life miserable for Bhanu, returns. He kidnaps Bhanu and places a [[cadaver]] in her home before faking an accident with a [[cooking gas]] [[gas cylinder|cylinder]], leading Ravi and his family to believe that Bhanu died in a kitchen accident. After that, Rathnavel brings Bhanu to his [[bungalow]] in an isolated area and locks her in a soundproof room. When Ravi goes to Rathnavel's house to get some [[life insurance]] papers, a series of clues lead him to find Bhanu. After distracting Rathnavel, Ravi calls the police and rescues Bhanu. Rathnavel is sent to a [[mental asylum]], where he later [[hanging|hangs himself]]. This seems to be a true story which happened in [[Andhra Pradesh]] in the late 1990s, and Rathnavel's (name changed) family members are still there in [[Kakinada]], but the movie ends with a happy note when we see that Ravi and Bhanu are still happily married and Bhanu is visibly [[pregnancy|pregnant]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]] as Ravichandran\n* [[Padmapriya Janakiraman]] as Bhanumathy (voice dubbed by [[Chinmayi]])\n* [[Nithin Sathya]] as Rathnavel Kalidas\n* [[Raaghav]] as Bhanu's brother\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Vincent Selvakumar\n* [[Suhasini]] as Gynecologist\n* [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Police\n* [[Premji Amaren|Premji]] as Ravichandran's friend\n* [[Jagan]] as Jegan, Rathnavel's friend\n* [[Crane Manohar]] as Ramachandran\n* Soundarya as Ramachandran's mother\n* M. Krishnamoorthy (Nagesh Krishnamoorthy) as Bhanu's father\n\n==Soundtrack==\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Satham Podathey\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 14 June 2007 (India)\n| recorded   = 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 28:36\n| label      = Hit Music\n| producer   = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| prev_title = [[Raju Bhai]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Thottal Poo Malarum]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n\nAfter eight years director [[Vasanth]] teamed up with composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] again for the musical score after creating the highly successful album of ''[[Poovellam Kettuppar]]'' (1999), which is considered to be Yuvan Shankar Raja's breakthrough album. The soundtrack, of ''Satham Podathey'', featuring 5 tracks overall, was released on 14 June 2007 at the Kamarajar Arangam in [[Chennai]] in a grand manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kollywoodtoday.com/news/sathumpodaathay-audio-launched/|title=Sathumpodaathay audio launched|publisher=kollywoodtoday.com|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> A [[live concert]] was conducted by Yuvan Shankar Raja, playing all the songs on stage, whereas the five songs were released by five music directors each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14471069|title=Yuvan`s `Isai Iravu`|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/satham-podathey-vasanth-160607.html|title=Satham Podathey: A musical treat|publisher=[[Oneindia]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist|\n|extra_column=Singer(s)\n|headline = Track-List\n|total_length=28:36\n|all_lyrics = [[Na. Muthukumar]]\n|title1=Azhagu Kutti Chellam|extra1= [[Shankar Mahadevan]] |length1= 5:48 \n|title2=O Indha Kaadhal|extra2=[[Adnan Sami]], Yuvan Shankar Raja|length2=5:30\n|title3=Pesugiren Pesugiren|extra3=[[Neha Bhasin]] |length3=5:30 |note3 = credited as \"[[Viva (band)|Viva Girls]]\"\n|title4=Entha Kuthiraiyil|extra4= [[Shreya Ghoshal]], [[Rahul Nambiar]]|length4=6:20 \n|title5=Kadhal Periyadha|extra5=[[Sudha Raghunathan]] |length5=5:28\n}}\n\n===Reception===\n\nThe music got rave reviews, praising Yuvan Shankar Raja's work. He was, in particular, lauded for making singers [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]] and [[Sudha Raghunathan]] render songs in different genres as they earlier never did,<ref name=\"Rediffreview\">{{cite web|url=http://ia.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/22sssp.htm|title=Sathum Podaathey has youthful music|publisher=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> whereas especially Raghunathan's first-time rendition of a [[Hip-hop]] song called \"Kadhal Periyadha\", was seen as a \"surprise item\",<ref name=\"Rediffreview\"/> cited as \"bringing out the [[Britney Spears]] in her\".<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/8130.html|title=Sathumpodaathay&nbsp;\u2014 Yuvan rocks|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> Moreover, the album itself was described as a \"pure musical delight\",<ref name=\"Oneindiareview\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/satham-podathey-music-review-080807.html|title=Satham Podathey&nbsp;\u2014 Music Review|publisher=[[Oneindia]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> whilst composer Yuvan Shankar himself was cited to be rocking.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\"/><ref name=\"Oneindiareview\"/> The songs gained immense popularity as well, particularly \"Pesugiren Pesugiren\" and \"O Indha Kaadhal\" were topping the charts for some time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/14/stories/2007091450110400.htm|title=Shhh... He\u2019s back|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-07-27|location=Chennai, India|date=2007-09-14}}</ref> Neha Bhasin was later awarded the Reliance Mobile Vijay TV Award for Best Female Playback Singer for the song \"Pesugiren Pesugiren\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starboxoffice.com/kollywood/vijayawards/about.html|title=Reliance Mobile Vijay Awards&nbsp;\u2014 The Awards Ceremony|publisher=starboxoffice.com|accessdate=2009-07-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726022319/http://www.starboxoffice.com/kollywood/vijayawards/about.html|archivedate=26 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1507349}}\n\n{{Vasanth}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s thriller films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vasanth]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Satham Podathey\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vasanth]]\n| producer       = C. Shanker<br />R. S. Senthil Kumar\n| writer         = [[Vasanth]]\n| starring       = [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]]<br />[[Padmapriya Janakiraman|Padmapriya]]<br />[[Nithin Sathya]]<br />[[Raaghav]]<br />[[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]]<br />[[Suhasini Mani Ratnam|Suhasini]]\n| music          = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cinematography = Dinesshkumaar\n| editing        = Sathisshkurosowaa\n| studio         = Kaivallya Entertainment\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2007|09|14}}\n| runtime        = 157 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Satham Podathey''''' ({{lang-en|Don't make a sound}}) is a 2007 Tamil [[psychological thriller film]] written and directed by [[Vasanth]] and produced by Shankar and Senthilnathan. It stars [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]], [[Padmapriya Janakiraman|Padmapriya]] and [[Nithin Sathya]] in the lead roles whilst [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]], [[Suhasini Mani Ratnam|Suhasini]], [[Premji Amaren|Premji]] and [[Raaghav]] play cameo roles. The film, which is based on a true incident, has music scored by [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], which received rave reviews. The film was released on 14 September 2007 to positive reviews. The film was simultaneously dubbed in [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] as  ''Kelkaatha Shabdam''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story revolves around Bhanumathy ([[Padmapriya]]) who gets married to Rathnavel Kalidas ([[Nithin Sathya]]), a guy who works in railways as a [[hockey]] player. He married Bhanu by hiding the facts that he is [[impotent]] and a recovering [[alcoholism|alcoholic]]. Soon, the relationship turns sour when the couple realizes that Rathnavel is impotent after a [[gynecology|gynecologist]] ([[Suhasini]]) tells them so. In spite of family pressures to get a mutual [[divorce]], the old-fashioned Bhanu decides to go ahead with the marriage by adopting a child. With the baby's arrival, Rathnavel unfortunately becomes more insecure and tells Bhanu that the child reminds him about his weakness. Unfortunately, all hell breaks loose when Bhanu realizes that her husband was an alcoholic who knew about his impotency and had betrayed her. Rathnavel, in his anger, beats up Bhanu until she is almost unconscious. A few days later, she files for a [[divorce]] and stays with her parents for some days. Bhanu later meets Ravichandran ([[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]]), a happy-go-lucky guy who is a friend of her brother ([[Raaghav]]). Ravi proposes to Bhanu, and they later get married, but Rathnavel, who had vowed to make life miserable for Bhanu, returns. He kidnaps Bhanu and places a [[cadaver]] in her home before faking an accident with a [[cooking gas]] [[gas cylinder|cylinder]], leading Ravi and his family to believe that Bhanu died in a kitchen accident. After that, Rathnavel brings Bhanu to his [[bungalow]] in an isolated area and locks her in a soundproof room. When Ravi goes to Rathnavel's house to get some [[life insurance]] papers, a series of clues lead him to find Bhanu. After distracting Rathnavel, Ravi calls the police and rescues Bhanu. Rathnavel is sent to a [[mental asylum]], where he later [[hanging|hangs himself]]. This seems to be a true story which happened in [[Andhra Pradesh]] in the late 1990s, and Rathnavel's (name changed) family members are still there in [[Kakinada]], but the movie ends with a happy note when we see that Ravi and Bhanu are still happily married and Bhanu is visibly [[pregnancy|pregnant]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]] as Ravichandran\n* [[Padmapriya Janakiraman]] as Bhanumathy (Voice Dubbed by [[Chinmayi]])\n* [[Nithin Sathya]] as Rathnavel Kalidas\n* [[Raaghav]] as Bhanu's brother\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Vincent Selvakumar\n* [[Suhasini]] as Gynecologist\n* [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Police\n* [[Premji Amaren|Premji]] as Ravichandran's friend\n* [[Jagan]] as Jegan (Rathnavel's friend)\n* [[Crane Manohar]] as Ramachandran\n* Soundarya as Ramachandran's mother\n* M. Krishnamoorthy (Nagesh Krishnamoorthy) as Bhanu's father\n\n==Soundtrack==\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Satham Podathey\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 14 June 2007 (India)\n| recorded   = 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 28:36\n| label      = Hit Music\n| producer   = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| prev_title = [[Raju Bhai]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Thottal Poo Malarum]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n\nAfter eight years director [[Vasanth]] teamed up with composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] again for the musical score after creating the highly successful album of ''[[Poovellam Kettuppar]]'' (1999), which is considered to be Yuvan Shankar Raja's breakthrough album. The soundtrack, of ''Satham Podathey'', featuring 5 tracks overall, was released on 14 June 2007 at the Kamarajar Arangam in [[Chennai]] in a grand manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kollywoodtoday.com/news/sathumpodaathay-audio-launched/|title=Sathumpodaathay audio launched|publisher=kollywoodtoday.com|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> A [[live concert]] was conducted by Yuvan Shankar Raja, playing all the songs on stage, whereas the five songs were released by five music directors each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14471069|title=Yuvan`s `Isai Iravu`|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/satham-podathey-vasanth-160607.html|title=Satham Podathey: A musical treat|publisher=[[Oneindia]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist|\n|extra_column=Singer(s)\n|headline = Track-List\n|total_length=28:36\n|all_lyrics = [[Na. Muthukumar]]\n|title1=Azhagu Kutti Chellam|extra1= [[Shankar Mahadevan]] |length1= 5:48 \n|title2=O Indha Kaadhal|extra2=[[Adnan Sami]], Yuvan Shankar Raja|length2=5:30\n|title3=Pesugiren Pesugiren|extra3=[[Neha Bhasin]] |length3=5:30 |note3 = credited as \"[[Viva (band)|Viva Girls]]\"\n|title4=Entha Kuthiraiyil|extra4= [[Shreya Ghoshal]], [[Rahul Nambiar]]|length4=6:20 \n|title5=Kadhal Periyadha|extra5=[[Sudha Raghunathan]] |length5=5:28\n}}\n\n===Reception===\n\nThe music got rave reviews, praising Yuvan Shankar Raja's work. He was, in particular, lauded for making singers [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]] and [[Sudha Raghunathan]] render songs in different genres as they earlier never did,<ref name=\"Rediffreview\">{{cite web|url=http://ia.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/22sssp.htm|title=Sathum Podaathey has youthful music|publisher=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> whereas especially Raghunathan's first-time rendition of a [[Hip-hop]] song called \"Kadhal Periyadha\", was seen as a \"surprise item\",<ref name=\"Rediffreview\"/> cited as \"bringing out the [[Britney Spears]] in her\".<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/musicreview/8130.html|title=Sathumpodaathay&nbsp;\u2014 Yuvan rocks|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> Moreover, the album itself was described as a \"pure musical delight\",<ref name=\"Oneindiareview\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/satham-podathey-music-review-080807.html|title=Satham Podathey&nbsp;\u2014 Music Review|publisher=[[Oneindia]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> whilst composer Yuvan Shankar himself was cited to be rocking.<ref name=\"Indiaglitzreview\"/><ref name=\"Oneindiareview\"/> The songs gained immense popularity as well, particularly \"Pesugiren Pesugiren\" and \"O Indha Kaadhal\" were topping the charts for some time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/14/stories/2007091450110400.htm|title=Shhh... He\u2019s back|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-07-27|location=Chennai, India|date=2007-09-14}}</ref> Neha Bhasin was later awarded the Reliance Mobile Vijay TV Award for Best Female Playback Singer for the song \"Pesugiren Pesugiren\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starboxoffice.com/kollywood/vijayawards/about.html|title=Reliance Mobile Vijay Awards&nbsp;\u2014 The Awards Ceremony|publisher=starboxoffice.com|accessdate=2009-07-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726022319/http://www.starboxoffice.com/kollywood/vijayawards/about.html|archivedate=26 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1507349}}\n\n{{Vasanth}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[